The Prague Stock Exchange fell to a minus at the end of trading
After a sharp fall in the morning, the Prague Stock Exchange corrected losses.
Transactions with ČEZ shares reached almost half of the daily trade.
The Prague Stock Exchange continued its decline on Monday as it fell by almost 6% from the start of Tuesday’s trading.
This time, the stock market is falling on Wall Street.
This reflects the market’s reaction to the result of the vote of the US House of Representatives, which refused to support the plan to stabilize the financial sector there.
The Fall of Stocks in Asia
Stocks in Asia fell dramatically on Tuesday, although the indices eventually wiped out some of the losses over the course of the day.
Hong Kong’s Hang Seng index has written off nearly four percent of its trading, but later erased some of the losses and reduced the decline to about 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises index, which tracks the movement of Chinese stocks on the Hong Kong stock exchange, fell by 3.8 percent, with markets closed in Shanghai.
Stocks on the Sydney Stock Exchange lost more than five percent, but eventually reduced losses to 4.3 percent.
The stock market in Taiwan fell by 3.6 percent, according to the index.
“The timing of the U.S. rescue is uncertain and will affect financial markets around the world,” said Joseph Yam, the head of Hong Kong’s monetary authority.
Hong Kong, despite being a part of China, sets its monetary policy independently, i.e. without dependence on the Chinese central bank.
Hong Kong’s interest rates are the same as those of the United States.
Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd said U.S. lawmakers should urgently return to negotiations and approve a proposal to support the financial system.
Other countries are also at risk of being affected.
The Bloodbath of American Action
The U.S. House of Representatives on Monday rejected a plan to support the financial system, which was to be spent up to $700 billion (nearly $12 trillion).
The lawmakers ignored President George Bush’s call to support the plan.
According to Bush, the plan would address the root causes of the financial crisis and help stabilize the entire economy.
U.S. stocks experienced a bloodbath on Monday, and major stock indices saw their biggest downturn in more than 20 years.
The Dow Jones index fell nearly seven percent, and the last time it fell was in 1987.
The index had already fallen before the vote, but as soon as it turned out that the bill had not passed in the House, the index was in free fall.
Congress backs down: U.S. government could pump $700 billion into banks
U.S. Congressional leaders and President George W. Bush's administration have agreed on a broader form of financial aid agreement for the U.S. financial system.
It will be voted on early next week.
U.S. lawmakers have made a breakthrough in talks to approve a $700 billion bailout plan for the U.S. financial system.
However, it has not yet been won.
Congress has to finalize some of the details of the deal before they can publish the final version of the bill and vote on it.
The plan to support the financial system will be discussed in the House of Representatives on Monday.
On Sunday, Barney Frank, chairman of the House Banking and Financial Services Committee, told Reuters.
According to sources, the plan could be voted on in the Senate first on Wednesday.
According to economists, the announcement that the rescue plan will be approved should be the first major psychological factor in the recovery of financial markets.
After that, however, there will be a "sober up" due to the complexity of the mechanisms that help the markets to achieve in practice.
Paulson: Plan must be effective
"We have made great progress.
We have resolved our differences over what the package looks like to stabilize the market," Democrat Nancy Pelosi told Bloomberg.
He said the final vote could take place on Sunday.
On Sunday, lawmakers met with U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson to give a definitive form to the government fund.
He should buy unsold mortgage assets from financial companies, which pull financial firms into heavy losses and threaten the stability of the entire system.
"We are on the verge of a definitive agreement on a plan that will work and must also be effective on the market.
We still need to continue with the recovery plan, but I think we’re there,” Paulson said.
Signal for Asian trading
The global financial crisis is hitting the stock markets, which are falling sharply.
Nevada Senator Harry Reid said lawmakers were trying to reach a deal in Congress on Sunday.
They want to reassure investors before trading in Asian financial markets, which are the first in the time zone where Congress’s decision could affect Monday’s trading.
However, it is not yet clear when the two houses of Congress will vote on the bill, or whether they can get stuck in the negotiations at the last minute.
Lawmakers are hoping it will be approved in the next few days.
However, the law will still undergo a number of changes.
The total amount allocated to the scheme is to be split into two parts.
The initial $350 billion is to be made available as soon as possible, as demanded by President George Bush.
However, Congress may block the release of the remaining amount if it feels that the program is not performing its function, in turn, another $100 billion and later the final $350 billion.
Bush praised the progress of the negotiations.
The president can veto the decision, but Congress can override it.
Despite these changes, however, the basic idea of the program, which was to raise funds to buy back bad mortgage securities, whose value has fallen because hundreds of thousands of Americans are unable to repay their mortgages, has remained.
"We worked everything out.
The House of Representatives should be able to vote on the bill on Sunday and the Senate on Monday," said Republican Senator Judd Gregg.
US President Bush is also pleased with the progress in the negotiations.
His spokesman, Tony Fratto, said Bush was pleased with Saturday's progress and appreciated the "two-party effort to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy."
Limitations of Gold Parachutes
Senate Banking Committee Chairman Christopher Dodd, the lead negotiator, said that lawmakers had agreed on responsibility for the money program, protecting taxpayers from losses, closing the concessions, timing the funding plan.
The new law is also intended to limit the so-called golden parachutes for directors of companies participating in the program and establishes a committee to supervise the fund.
It should be managed by the Ministry of Finance.
"We've worked very hard on this, and we've made great progress toward a deal that works and is useful for the market and for all Americans," Paulson said.
The plan also includes assistance for homeowners who have repayment problems.
The government should negotiate new installments on mortgages it buys, in order to reduce the monthly cost of installments for borrowers and allow them to keep their homes.
Marek: Psychological help
The proposed plan is a good idea, according to chief economist Patrio Finance David Mark, but it will be very difficult to implement.
"That's because we don't know what mechanism and at what price the problem assets will be bought back.
This will determine how the financial sector and the government divide their losses,” Marek told news server iHNed.cz this week.
Whether the plan will be approved now or early next week is not that important, according to Mark.
"It is much more important that the congressmen agree this week that they support this plan and that they will sanctify it as soon as possible.
The psychological significance of the agreement on the approval is the most important at the moment," Marek stressed.
Clash on the blade of a knife: MP3 players against mobiles.
We will advise you how to choose
While almost every mobile phone can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can make phone calls.
It seems that it is better to just buy a phone.
However, there are plenty of reasons to buy a separate player.
The choice entirely depends on the method of use and the demands of the future owner.
It is probably difficult to get a top expensive turntable at home to listen to the latest Maxim Turbulenc album on it.
On the one hand, such music products are not based on LP records and there is no objective reason for this from a qualitative point of view.
However, if there are vinyls with art rock, jazz or blues on your shelves, you probably dream of such a turntable.
It is the same with music on the go, i.e. music compressed, simplified - music in MP3.
There are also price and quality categories.
For some, it may be unacceptable to spend eight thousand crowns on a player, just as a Pink Floyd fan may hardly bite the headphones for twenty crowns from the market.
Two extremes, between which there is enough space for everyone.
The choice is wide.
It also depends on the battery life
Some top music players can do much more than just play music, but what most mobiles can't do.
No device is as universal as a phone.
In addition to its primary functions, calling and texting, it can play music and video, record both, have a better, worse camera, and maybe even navigate.
And if you consider smartphones and communicators, you will have a small computer in your pocket.
It's a small miracle, because no refrigerator can grill and no television can photograph anything.
The universality of the mobile phone also brings disadvantages.
The more functions you use on your phone, the sooner the indicator on the display sends you to the charger.
And playing music is one of the biggest energy grabs.
Few phones can play music for more than ten to twelve hours, usually much less.
In this respect, music players (especially the simplest ones) are significantly more powerful.
For cheap mobile phones, you should expect that they will not play for more than a few hours.
If you still call here and there, get another charger to work for sure - this also applies to more expensive devices.
For MP3 players, you will not have this problem, even the worst ones will last at least 9 hours of continuous operation on a single charge.
Another problem occurs when recording music to a mobile phone.
Unfortunately, only a limited number of devices have a universal USB connector, and not all of them can be directly connected to a computer without special software.
Of course, music can be recorded directly to the memory card, but only a few card readers can cope without reduction with the miniature memory cards that are used in mobile phones.
With the exception of iPod players, you do not need any special software.
Just fill the device with music via USB from your computer.
Most mobile phones and players already create their own music library sorted by artist name, album title, genre or user rating.
Some devices display only the directory tree structure similar to Windows Explorer, and some can do both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smartphones with an operating system).
Players are easier to use, mobiles are more efficient
When choosing a particular device, be interested in battery life, memory capacity, quality and type of audio output and, of course, comfort of operation.
If music is primarily a backdrop and you listen to it only briefly every day, for example on a tram, you can use any mobile phone that plays MP3.
Almost any cell phone can do that.
You don’t even have to watch what music formats your phone or player can do.
MP3 can handle all and the vast majority of music that gets to you will be in this format.
It is one of the most popular and in addition to it, the vast majority of devices can also handle music in WMA format.
AAC (the format used by Apple and its iPods) is less common.
Better mobile phones also allow you to buy music online, for example.
Just visit the relevant website of the operator (or other provider) and buy the song or album.
This service could already be a strong argument in itself for the purchase of a music mobile phone.
Unfortunately, the offer of operators is poor and is usually limited to fast-paced radio hits.
Prices are also not the lowest.
However, it is generally assumed that this method of selling music (whether via GSM, the Internet or wireless Internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people carry their cell phone with them.
Whenever you want to listen to something, you can feel the phone in your pocket, while the MP3 player lies forgotten at home.
However, it still depends on whether you always carry headphones or at least wired handsfree.
If not, you can use an integrated speaker, which has almost every mobile, but only a minimum of MP3 players.
Perhaps the biggest advantage of music phones will be the price.
The cheapest ones usually cost under three thousand.
For three and four thousand crowns you will get a very decent walkman.
Most of the time, however, you will be limited by the lack of output to regular headphones.
The best and technically most equipped phones with a 3.5 mm socket for ordinary headphones cost up to fifteen thousand.
The advantage of the players is, among other things, easy operation.
The simplest - not necessarily the cheapest (see our selection) - players can be controlled by everyone.
The minimum of functions, the similarity of control with a previously common cassette player or turntable is obvious.
There is no risk of collision in the form of accidentally switched on mobile internet and subsequently a giant account for data transmission.
Which device to use
Even the cheapest mobile phones (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for removable memory cards (type M2, microSD, etc.).
Even with the purchase of the relevant card, you can fit into two thousand crowns.
But be careful.
For basic models, only cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB are supported.
Only the most expensive can cope with 8 GB of memory.
If you already have a mobile phone and want to buy a cheap MP3 player, reach for Cowon, Creative, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or iriver.
According to the capacity (max. 2 GB) you do not need to spend more than 1 100 crowns.
If you are a more demanding listener, it is better to use specialized mobile phones - walkmans (Sony Ericsson, some Nokias and Samsungs).
These devices have separate control buttons for MP3 and the comfort of operation is thus close to a separate MP3 player.
Sony Ericsson, whose Walkman phones have the same user interface as the separately sold MP3 players.
The same service and in the same price range up to four thousand crowns, but with a larger memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and battery life (normally 15 hours, up to a maximum of 35 hours), will take MP3 players away from the above-mentioned brands.
The first virtual operator will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite advanced and our operators offer practically all services as their partners in Western Europe.
Still, we are missing something here - a virtual operator that would force the classic ones to become cheaper.
Maybe he won't be long.
We have written on Mobil.cz many times about the fact that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
This was confirmed by the CTU, which pointed out that the price of SMS is higher in our country than in the rest of the Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the field of regulation of roaming charges, a paradoxical situation may occur - for some customers of Czech mobile operators SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that really wants to fight.
Perhaps it sounds paradoxical, we have three mobile networks and penetration well over 100%.
Mobile operators, on the other hand, like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
Pavel Dvořák, the chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunication Office (ČTÚ), often points out that there is no place for another operator in the Czech Republic.
It is probably true that a classic operator with its own network probably does not have many chances (by the way, he would hardly look for frequencies anymore).
But there is another option - a virtual operator.
It was the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that brought a significant reduction in prices, which classic operators had to react to.
At the same time, before the launch of pike such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile, similar voices sounded in the UK as in our country.
However, it turned out that the place for such operators is and can be really successful.
We don’t have to go too far for examples.
In February this year, we informed you about the launch of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, this operator has managed to gain more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator there.
Mobilking is backed by the Penta financial group, which owns, among others, U:fona in the Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on a much more specific target group.
In order for them to work effectively, they need far fewer customers than a traditional operator.
They do not entail relatively high costs for the construction, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
In the world, virtual operators usually profile themselves as low-cost - they offer cheap calls and SMS, but this is often balanced by a narrower range of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half cheaper than its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can be quite a good move to bet on an innovative target group.
This operator focuses specifically on men.
"The right guys choose Mobilking - an operator they like and can trust," says David Seibertz, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, operating the virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether a similar concept as in Poland could be caught up in our country.
Vodafone spokesperson Miroslav Čepický doubts this: "The Czech market is relatively small for the segment approach on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition, it is relatively saturated in terms of service offer."
In the Czech Republic no chance, say mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual mobile operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations do not look very promising.
Rather, Mobilking will be launched in other countries of our region," Jana Studničková, a spokeswoman for the financial group Penta, said in a telephone interview for Mobil.cz.
Indirectly, it confirmed that the current mobile operators in the Czech Republic are definitely not in favour of this idea.
On the contrary, it tries to do everything to ensure that no potential competitor is created.
GTS Novera has long been interested in launching a virtual mobile operator, which would like to take the next step to become a real competitor of Telefonica O2 in the field of corporate customers.
“We are very interested in being able to offer our customers not only fixed but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner the better.
We have repeatedly discussed this possibility with all Czech mobile operators.
We have already made progress with some of them in the negotiations," says Pavel Kaidl, the group's spokesman.
Maybe it’s for better times.
From unofficial information, it seems that the first virtual operator should be expected by the end of the year.
For now, however, its creation is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
"At the moment, we do not believe that there is room on the Czech market for the emergence of a full-fledged virtual operator.
The Czech market is very specific compared to other markets.
So far, we have not been approached by any entity with a complex and serious project in this area," said Vlastimil Sršeň from the Press Department of Telefónika O2 in a statement to Mobil.cz.
Other operators also refer to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobile spokesperson Martina Kemrová adds in rare agreement with O2’s statement: “So far, we have not seen any viable and mutually beneficial business project on which to build further.”
He adds: “There will be hardly any virtual operator on the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
At this point, we would have to have a concrete agreement on the table to be able to think in this short term."
Vodafone focuses its attention on meeting the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický says: “By negotiating with potential virtual operators, we are open, especially in the area of cost sharing and infrastructure.
This is what we consider to be the most beneficial for our customers.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is to find a partner for building a shared network for fast mobile internet.”
Responsible authorities - with operators one hand
The procedure of mobile operators can be easily understood, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would lead to a decrease in prices and thus a decrease in their profits.
Why make it easier for such a competitor?
The fact that when operators are interested in something, they can pull together is also evidenced by the tug around the creation of U:fon.
Probably the biggest pressure towards CTU went at the time of the creation of U:fona from T-Mobile.
This is evidenced by publicly available information from the ČTÚ website.
Now, however, U:fon can be used as an argument for not allowing a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová commented: “More recently, the competitive environment of the mobile market has been enhanced by the entry of the fourth mobile operator into the market.
Given the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is clear that the entry of another player would place high demands on him and, above all, on his services."
However, due to this approach of mobile operators, the total lack of interest of the Czech regulatory authorities is striking.
It is not just the position of the CTU, which unfortunately in the Czech Republic - unlike the UK and other developed countries - does not have the power to interfere in competition.
These belong exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Competition (ÚOHS).
But he took a typical stance on the issue.
“The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible after the conclusion of a contract between the mobile operator and the virtual operator for the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
No such contract has been concluded so far, because the offer of potential candidates was probably not interesting enough for classical operators," said Kristián Chalupa from the Department of External Relations of the Office for Human Rights in response to our question.
From the representatives of the operators, this statement is probably not surprising.
It is more than respectable from an authority that is supposed to represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, to ensure that no one abuses their position on the market.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: "In foreign countries, where virtual operators normally operate, we can observe that their entry into the market has contributed to a reduction in prices for mobile telephone services."
Obviously, however, the pressure on the proper functioning of the market environment and the fall in prices are not among the interests of the Office.
In fact, what is shocking about the whole case is the touching resonance of the three mobile operators, which results from their reactions.
The question of whether it is really just a coincidence is offered all by itself.
As well as the exact same price of petrol at petrol stations, it is certainly just a matter of chance and fierce competition.
"The Office has not found any signs of anti-competitive behaviour in this matter and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position and therefore does not have a correspondingly increased responsibility for their actions in the market.
The necessary tools to open the mobile market to virtual operators are probably also missing from the telecom regulator," Chalupa said in a statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of many controversial points.
There is, of course, an analysis of the relevant markets carried out by CTU, according to which telecommunications is the only market from the point of view of competition.
In such a market, of course, none of the Czech operators has a dominant position.
However, some legal experts offer a different perspective - the creation of a virtual operator always requires the consent of the network operator.
And the mobile operator - quite logically - has a monopoly on its network.
So in a certain segment it necessarily has to be dominant.
Even if we do not admit this argument, it should be at least alarming for the Office that three mobile operators act in a strikingly similar way.
At the same time, complaints from a number of interested parties (including GTS Novera) show that they encounter very similar obstacles when dealing with all operators.
Placing responsibility on CTU is then a fairly common trick in telecommunications, with which the Office puts its hands away from the whole matter.
We have met him in several similar cases.
Unfortunately, the recently adopted amendment to the Telecommunications Act did not succeed in extending the powers of the CTU to the area of competition in telecommunications, although many experts promised to improve the situation.
This must be known more than well by the representatives of the Office, but apparently their interests are elsewhere.
That's what happens when no one's looking.
At the same time, the functioning of some pseudo-virtual operators remains unnoticed, of which there are several in the Czech mobile networks.
These are companies issuing their own price lists of mobile telephone services, but they are only partially public.
This is usually a multi-level marketing company.
Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile phone services.
The prices of these companies usually reach only the chosen ones.
The magic lies in the fact that the company acts towards the operator as a classic corporate customer who orders a large number of SIM cards.
As a significant customer, you will then receive special price (and other) offers.
The problem is that the terms and conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit similar resale.
"If there are cases you are talking about, it could be a violation of the contractual terms that we would deal with and could result in the termination of cooperation with the company," Kemrová said.
However, it is unlikely that such activities would not reach the responsible people from mobile operators.
Especially in the case of the three mentioned companies, there may be thousands of customers.
None of the operators opposes such a procedure.
They make significant profits from the activities of these companies and, unlike real virtual operators, they do not threaten them with their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický points out the possible problems: "The law allows such speculation, however, only a negligible percentage of customers use the services of these companies.
In addition, they must accept that the SIM card in their phone is not in their name, so they cannot have it fully as regular customers of mobile operators."
But that should be at least weird.
In addition, another question is raised for the OHS.
If mobile operators turn a blind eye to a similar procedure, why are they blocking the creation of a virtual operator?
It should be added that the Office has relatively strong powers to detect such activity, and if it does not want to, it may not be satisfied with the operators’ explanation that they are unaware of such a thing and their terms and conditions prohibit it.
When will we not be the most expensive?
As it has fallen several times in the text, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has brought a noticeable decrease in prices for services.
In virtually all countries where virtual operators were created, classical operators tried to defend their creation more or less.
Their arguments were practically identical - too small or too saturated market, problems with the quality of services, etc.
In developed countries, however, it was in these moments that regulators intervened, defending not the interests of mobile operators, but their customers.
Whether through formal measures or informal pressure, they then achieved the creation of the first virtual operator and more were packed onto it.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators are tossing the whole case around like a hot potato.
From our experience, we can not get rid of the impression that the ambiguity in competence in these cases is more than convenient for them.
But let's not flip.
If the behind-the-scenes information is correct and the virtual operator will appear with us really soon, the Czech mobile market may move again.
If one of the operators has allowed the emergence of a virtual mobile operator, it will be difficult for the Office to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of other interested parties.
And maybe we'll stop calling the price than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech national anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best one
Listen to four performances of the new version of the Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek on the occasion of the Day of Czech Statehood presented new recordings of the national anthem Where My Home.
The anthem was newly recorded by the National Theatre Orchestra under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions - with male or female solo singing, in choral version and instrumental version.
The song was performed by Kateřina Knezínková and Adam Plachetka.
The hymn was edited by Otakar Jeremiáš and Jaroslav Krček.
On the server iHNed.cz you can listen to all four versions.
Bělohlávek considers the Czech national song to be one of the most beautiful hymens.
He had previously told Czech Radio that he had deliberately chosen singers with young representative voices who were distinctive and popular for singing solo variants.
"From the beginning, I tried to make sure that both of them, and then also the congregation, had a clear diction, that the text was well understood, that they were in harmony," he said.
The Czech National Anthem will celebrate its 175th anniversary next year.
The song Where my home was first played in 1834 on the boards of the Estates Theatre in the original Czech play Fidlovačka by Josef Kajetán Tyl accompanied by music by František Škroup.
It gained popularity and people spontaneously took it as their own.
After the establishment of Czechoslovakia in 1918, the first verse of the song became a natural part of the national anthem.
It remained one of the seven state symbols even after the establishment of the independent Czech Republic.
