Prague public transport will take a ride on the chip for the first time on Wednesday
Wednesday, October 1, 2008 will go down in the history of the Prague Transport Company as the date when the first passengers will board the metro, trams and buses, who will have an electronic ticket in their pocket instead of a paper ticket.
At the moment, it is possible to buy about one hundred thousand people who own an Opencard chip card.
Passengers can buy a 30-day and 90-day and annual coupon (which will be valid from 1 January 2009) and have it uploaded to their chip card in the information centres and workplaces of the Transport Company in the metro stations Muzeum, Můstek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka.
Coupons can also be bought online from yesterday on the website of the Transport Company www.dpp.cz.
More than 400 customers used the service in the afternoon.
Those who start using the online store can definitely forget about the dispensing windows in metro stations, where they have had to regularly stand in long queues for paper tickets.
They buy the coupon online and upload it to their Opencard at one of the 13 branches of the Municipal Library.
"In these places, there is a counter with trained staff available to passengers to help with online shopping and also upload a purchased coupon to their card," said Martin Opatrný, spokesman for the project.
In addition to libraries, it will also be possible to upload electronic coupons to Opencard in self-service vending machines, which are mounted in several subway vestibules.
What do these automatons look like?
They are red, reminiscent of ticket markers and passengers may have noticed them in the metro stations Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"There are now five in the city, but by the end of the year there should be eighty," he added.
The coupon will check the slot driver's place
Operation of the machines that will start working tomorrow is simple.
Just insert the Opencard chip card into them and the previously paid coupon will be uploaded to it.
Electronic coupons from tomorrow are valid not only in the capital, but also in its surroundings.
That is, in suburban trains and bus lines with the number 300 to 499, which are used mainly by residents of Central Bohemian municipalities.
"In trains included in the Prague Integrated Transport, conductors are equipped with card readers, using which they check the time and zone validity of coupons," Filip Drápal from the Ropid organization, which compiles timetables for Prague's public transport, explained.
Suburban buses have card readers built into the cash register of the driver.
When boarding, it is necessary not only to show the chip card to the driver, but also to attach the Opencard to the designated place on the side of the cash register.
This will allow the driver to check the validity of the recorded coupons.
"If a passenger needs to verify the validity of the recorded coupons, there is nothing easier than to ask the driver for this information," he added.
Passengers who do not travel by suburban buses and will not remember when their coupon expires can go back to the self-service machines where card coupons are recorded.
Here, information about the validity of their documents will be displayed on the display of the device.
The Sudetenland wanted a referendum.
The Sudeten Germans in 1945 asked for the incorporation of the Šumava into the United States.
This follows from a letter stored in the collections of the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we want to live under the patronage of the United States of America.
It is said that in 1945 some groups of Sudeten Germans turned to the President of the United States with such a wish.
This follows, among other things, from a letter that has been preserved in a private archive and is now stored in the collections of the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
The Germans of Český Krumlov are asking the American president in a letter not to allow the return of the "Šumava County" - taken by Hitler on the basis of the Munich Agreement - back to Czechoslovakia.
"We have understood the situation correctly and we want to be really sure that American troops are coming to German territory not as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators," the letter reads.
Since joining Czechoslovakia supposedly gives the Sudeten Germans - with the knowledge of the Czech national character - hope only for brutality, ruthlessness, misunderstanding, oppression and slavery, the authors of the letter of the American president plead to take over the protectorate over Šumava for the present and eternal times.
“We cannot believe that, regardless of the opinion of a quarter of a million inhabitants, you would grant this territory to a foreign state, which oppresses and disproves minorities and nothing, has contributed nothing to the victory of the Allies,” the letter reads.
The reason why the authors cannot sign up is allegedly fear of the vindictiveness of the "Czech oppressors".
