Even rats have feelings.
When a rat or a cockroach flees from danger, does that mean that they also feel fear?
Neuroscientist Joseph LeDoux believes that many animals have feelings.
But how can we verify that they feel the same way when they behave like us?
The Internet magazine "Edge" has been publishing the contributions of well-known scientists for several years.
SPIEGEL ONLINE in its series presents selected answers to the question "What do you consider to be true without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have feelings and other states of consciousness without me or anyone else being able to prove it until now, when we can't even prove that other people have consciousness.
But in this case, we can at least hope, because all human brains have the same basic configuration.
However, once we start to deal with a different kind and open up questions of perception or general consciousness, we enter an impassable terrain, because the hardware does not match.
When a rat gets in danger, it does the same thing as many other animals: it pretends to be dead, flees, or attacks.
People behave in a similar way, which some scientists judge to be comparable to subjective experience.
But I don't believe that.
Two aspects of brain structure make it difficult to transfer our subjective experience to the experience of animals.
This is partly because the circuits associated with human consciousness almost always include the lateral prefrontal cortex (due to its share of short-term memory and executive or control functions).
This vast area is much more developed in humans than in other primates, and appears to be completely absent in other creatures.
At least for those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, among them knowing who we are, and being able to plan and make decisions, there is reason to believe that man is even different from other primates.
Another dramatic peculiarity could hide the linguistic nature of a person: because so much of his perception is connected with language, it is often said that consciousness depends on it.
In this case, we can exclude animals.
But even if language consciousness did not matter, language would certainly influence it, so that animal consciousness, however constructed, would probably differ from most states of our consciousness.
Therefore, it is difficult to find out what consciousness looks like in other animals.
When, as something internal and subjective, it is impossible to even measure itself, due to the special hardware, to analyze it on the basis of our own experience, we are faced with great problems.
Most of my inferences relate to the content of conscious experience, but there is another aspect of consciousness that should be more scientifically accessible.
It would be possible to study the processes in the consciousness of animals regardless of their content, and this is exactly what is happening in studies of short-term memory in primates, especially on the example of visualization.
But this approach, pursued by Christof Koch and Francis Crick, focuses on neural correlates of consciousness rather than causal mechanisms: both may be identical, but they may not be either.
Interestingly, this approach also emphasizes the importance of non-frontal cortex for the realization of visualization.
What does this mean for feelings?
I deduce them from the fact that the emotional system, such as the fear system, is activated in the brain conscious of its own activity.
What we refer to as “fear” is the mental state we find ourselves in when the activity of a defense system localized in the brain (or its consequences, such as body reactions) uses operational memory.
Seen from this angle, feelings are closely related to those areas of the cortex that distinguish primates, especially humans.
In connection with linguistic nature, there is a subtle gradation of perception, because through words and grammar we can distinguish and categorize states in order to attribute them to others alongside ourselves.
In contrast, Antonio Damasio believes that feelings arise from more primitive activities in areas of the cortex and brain stem devoted to bodily sensations, similar to Jaak Pankseep, who, however, focuses more on the brain stem.
Since this network has not changed much in the course of human evolution, it could easily participate in the sensations perceived by multiple animal genera.
In theory, I can't argue with that, but I think it's unprovable.
Pankseep argues that what appears to us to be fear in rats and humans probably feels the same way: But how can it be verified, Pankseep goes on to say, that rats and humans feel the same when they behave similarly?
The cockroach flees from danger - does he also feel fear?
From my point of view, the mere similarity of behavior cannot prove the sameness of experience.
It is true that neural comparisons move us further: rats and humans have similar brain strains, while cockroaches do not have brains.
But is the brain stem responsible for feelings?
And even if it could be proved in man: how would we want to prove it in rats?
I think rats and other mammals, maybe even cockroaches (who knows?), have feelings.
But I really don't know how to prove it.
And since their feelings are probably fundamentally different from ours (because human consciousness rests on special circuits and on the tongue), I prefer to study emotional behavior rather than emotional perception of rats.
In any case, in this case, we can see progress at the neural level if we measure the same in rats and humans.
Just as in rats I do not examine language and consciousness, nor do I examine feelings, for I do not know if they exist.
It can be considered shortsighted, but I prefer to move forward rather than repeatedly throw myself against the wall.
I am a practical emotionalist.
