In the past two weeks, commodity markets have been rocked by financial turmoil on Wall Street, as well as a pair of powerful hurricanes in the Gulf of Mexico.
After peaking at $145.29 a barrel in July, prices fell to nearly $90 a barrel earlier this month, then jumped again on a wave of massive financial market uncertainty.
The anxiety gripped investors again on Monday, even after the congressional presidency announced that it had reached an agreement over the weekend on the largest rescue plan in history.
This report was overshadowed by fresh fears that the financial crisis was far from over.
In the latest episode of progressing decay, the government announced that Citigroup would acquire the banking arm of Wachovia Corporation.
Meanwhile, the Belgian, Dutch and Luxembourg governments partially nationalized the European financial conglomerate Fortis.
Analysts at Barclays Capital said the frantic weekend negotiations that led to the plan to save the economy "show themselves unable to revive the mood in the market".
As the economic situation worsens, demand for commodities, including oil, is expected to decline.
“The outlook for the global stock, interest rate and exchange rate markets has been highly uncertain,” Deutsche Bank analysts wrote in a report to investors.
“We believe that commodities will not be able to escape the infection.
From a commodity perspective, our biggest concern is to what extent the American virus will spread around the world, and especially to China."
Analysts at the bank cut their expectations for next year, as oil consumption fell due to slower economic growth, and lowered their 2009 gasoline price forecasts by about 20%.
Wild ride in the second quarter broke the team's record
After spending more time in the Jets over the past eight seasons than anyone else, defensive player Shaun Ellis thought he’d seen it all.
Then on Sunday, he watched the development of the second quarter, in which the Jets turned the scoreless game into a graceful ride.
“I’ve never seen anything like it,” Ellis said.
The second quarter began after the Jets and the Arizona Cardinals matched the grim clouds above them with their troubled game.
Then quarterback Brett Favre sent Laveranese Coles on a 12-yard touchdown sprint, perfecting the afternoon in which their gradually developing collaboration moved miles forward.
Favre sent Coles out in this quarter for another two touchdowns, including the one in which the cornerback fell, and another 10 seconds before the halftime game.
"It wasn't anything special," Favre told Coles about all his passes.
“He’s a damn good player.
We communicated well, no matter what people thought.”
While Favre and Coles were pitching, the defense attacked Cardinals quarterback Kurt Warner.
Cornerback Darelle Revis intercepted a stray throw and returned it 32 yards for a touchdown.
Safety Eric Smith picked up another pass and intercepted it.
Linebacker David Bowens forced Warner to fumble.
The last loss of the ball, the fumble that Bowens forced, was perhaps the best ever.
The Cardinals got to the ball 10 seconds before the end, and after the Jets got the ball back, Jay Feely kicked a 20-yard field goal, thus gaining a 34-0 lead.
That's the most the Jets have ever won in a quarter.
Jets coach Eric Mangini, when asked to describe the madness, said, "Second quarter or third quarter?"
When told that both - the Jets allowed 21 points in the third quarter with no answer - Mangini said, "I can tell you that I enjoyed the second quarter much more than the third.
A lot of points fell in a short period of time."
The rested Gebreselassie improved his world record
Haile Gebreselassie from Ethiopia once again showed why many consider him the best long-distance runner ever when he broke his own world record in the Berlin Marathon on Sunday, becoming the first person to run a 26.2-mile race under two hours and four minutes.
By winning on a pleasantly flat track in 2:03:59, he overtook by 27 seconds his previous time of 2:04:26, which he ran last year in Berlin.
Gebreselassie, who is 35, has set the 26th world record of his career, which is truly incredibly wide - he has broken the world record or at least is a world champion at all distances from the metric mile to the marathon.
Last month, Gebreselassie missed an Olympic marathon in Beijing because he was worried - perhaps too alarmed in hindsight - that air pollution would irritate his asthma problems.
Instead, he promised to run in Berlin.
In almost perfect conditions - sunny and 48 degrees at the start, 55 degrees at the finish - Gebreselassie won on Sunday with a lightning-fast average of 4 minutes and 43 seconds per mile.
As track runners like Gebreselassie and Paul Tergat of Kenya focused on longer runs, the marathon record fell more than two minutes in the past decade, since Ronaldo da Costa of Brazil won in Berlin in a time of 2:06:05 in 1998.
After Sunday's victory, Gebreselassie told reporters that he had cramps in his calf two weeks ago and missed a week of training.
The break seemed to be more of a wake-up call than a hold-up.
"I'm so happy," Gebreselassie told reporters.
"Everything was perfect.
A week ago I started again and I was a little in doubt today, but everything was fine."
He has also been criticized - mainly in Kenya, Ethiopia's East African rival - for allegedly over-planning his races, generally evading the world's marathon rushes, relying on drivers as if it were a track race, and setting world records above a sense of competition.
But this criticism can hardly diminish Gebreselassie's immense running qualities.
Maintained at the pace of the four Kenyans reached Gebreselassie's half in a time of 1:02:04.
After the drivers dropped out, Gebreselassie was constantly chased by two elite Kenyan runners James Kwambai and Charles Kamathi.
A little earlier than three miles before the finish, Gebreselassie made his last run and escaped Kwambai, who then ran in second place in 2:05:36 time, improving his personal best by almost five minutes.
Kamathi finished third in 2:07:48.
In the women's race, the excellent year ended with the seventh fastest time in the history of 2:19:19 Irina Mikitienkova, a native of Kazakhstan, who is now a German citizen.
The record time of 2:15:25 is held by Paula Radcliffe from Great Britain.
The 36-year-old Mikitienko won the London Marathon at 2:24:14 last spring.
She missed the Beijing Games due to what was described as a back injury, but recovered and won in Berlin and in the third marathon she ever ran, improving her personal maximum by almost five minutes.
She ran the race cleverly and thoughtfully: she let the four Ethiopian and Kenyan female runners escape to a big lead and then dragged them down after about 18 1/2 miles.
Askale Tafa Magarsa of Ethiopia finished second in 2:21:31 and Helene Kiprop of Kenya finished third in 2:25:01.
The Pride and Obstacles of Black Life in a Separate City
Hidden among the sprawling amusement parks of greater Orlando, a few miles from everything shiny, noisy, and huge, lies a quiet city where the pride and rigor of African-American life comes alive.
Eatonville, the first completely black city to be incorporated into the state, and where Zora Neale Hurston spent her childhood, is no longer as simple as she described it in 1935: "a city of five lakes, three croquet courts, three hundred brown skins, three hundred good swimmers, enough guacamole, two schools, and no prison."
Now it is a place of pilgrimage.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee came to the annual Zora! Eatonville Festival to pay their respects to Hurston, the most famous female writer of the Harlem Renaissance.
The city she described remains a sideline, though she made it a stopover for tourists by including it in a Florida tourist guide created by the Federal Writers project from the time of the economic crisis.
It is still as independent, dignified, and private as it was in the 1930s when Hurston wrote that rural blacks in Florida often resisted and did not share their true feelings with a white man who "knows so little about us that he doesn't even know what he's missing."
Even today, in a year when black presidential candidate Senator Barack Obama is calling for an open discussion of races, many locals remain wary of foreign perspectives.
“We’re paying close attention to how our story is told,” says Hortense Jones, 59, who has lived here since birth and is a member of the city’s oldest parish.
"It has to be right."
Eatonville has long been characterized as a paradox of triumph and effort.
It is both a historical model of black ascension and a community of nearly 2,400 people where the poverty rate is twice the national average.
It is a center of literature, but also an oak-shadowed example of Southern rural black culture - sometimes despised, sometimes lauded - that emerged from American slavery.
Not surprisingly, the people here are both proud and protective.
And the worry about the idea of Eatonville really started with Zora, which is the only way the Hurstons are called here.
She introduced her hometown to the world through cordial books full of dialects such as "Mules and Men" (1935) and "Their Eyes Were Watching God" (1937).
Five paragraphs of the Florida Tourist Guide turned the city a short distance into Route 17, which leads through the often-passed center of Florida, into a stage of black history and human drama.
With a big drumbeat in both life and literature, Hurston led the reader to the store of Eatonville's first mayor, Joe Clark, and then turned to more personal places.
"To the left of the road," she wrote, "is a white brown-decorated modern national school with well-maintained yards and pitches, which is always looked after by Howard Miller, though he cannot read or write much."
She also mentioned the widow's new husband Dash, writing that Lee Glenn "sells drinks of all kinds and anything at all that fits into a one-hour hotel."
So in just a few hundred words, Hurston linked Eatonville to self-government, but also to illiteracy, remarriage, and sex.
This clearly wasn't a typical Fodor's publishing house.
In fact, it wasn’t a portrait that everyone would appreciate.
"Zora said it the way it was," says 90-year-old Ella Dinkins, one of the chorus of Johnson's Girls, who Hurston made immortal by quoting men who sang dirty songs about their beauty.
"Some people didn't like it," she added.
Hurston is still remembered here as a chippy eccentric who often returned after her family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
Seventy-year-old Augustus Franklin remembers that most of the time, when she arrived in the city, she arrived unannounced in a huge Chevrolet, smoking and wearing pants in a city that even today is proud of its dignified dress code.
Most residents were fascinated, Franklin said, but many sneered.
"People have always liked to see Zoroa," Franklin said.
But, he added, swinging on a chair on the back terrace overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized, "she never stayed too long."
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were taken out of print.
Eatonville seemed to have forgotten her along with the rest of the world.
Although she was once a literary star, a contemporary of Langston Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an unmarked grave in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she had previously lived.
There were no major mourning ceremonies or large public readings at Eatonville.
"I don't think they understood either its importance to the world or its legacy," said Valerie Boyd, author of Hurston's 2003 biography Wrapped in Rainbows.
The change came in the 1980s.
Orange County officials wanted to stretch the city's five-lane highway instead of Kennedy Boulevard, a local two-lane main road.
Orlando's sprawl has already pushed Interstate 4 through the western edge of the city.
The proposal came at a time when Eatonville was still coming out of a difficult historical period.
Forced integration, along with other things, ended the relatively idyllic isolation of this community.
In the 1950s, the race-mixing struggle brought hatred to the threshold of the community.
"At the time, a bunch of white guys, they came in and threw oranges and stuff at people who were sitting on the side," Franklin said.
“We actually had a woman who was killed.
They threw a melon out of the car."
In a 1955 letter to The Orlando Sentinel, Hurston challenged the Supreme Court's demand for forced integration and declared his decision in the Brown v. Education Chamber case to be "insulting rather than glorifying to my race."
Residents now say that desegregation of schools, while positive in some areas, has reduced cohesion in Eatonville and undermined the youth's courage.
"Black kids were used to hugging -- I remember that -- you hugged your teacher in the morning, you hugged your teacher in the evening," said N. Y. Nathiri, daughter of Ella Dinkins and executive director of the nonprofit group Preserve the Eatonville Community.
This lasted until the teachers and pupils came from the same place, she added.
"You don't hug your white teacher because your white teacher -- I mean, there's a cultural barrier," Ms. Nathiri said.
Civil rights, however, helped to create space for many more Zora Neale Hurston - black writers, actors and artists who, like her, rose above prejudices with reckless self-confidence and quotes such as "How can anyone deny the pleasure of my presence!
I don't understand."
In 1975, Alice Walker reached Hurston's unmarked grave and began fighting to revive her reputation.
Five years later, the celebrated biography of Hurston by Robert E. Hemenway came to the shelves in bookstores, re-entering it into the American canon.
The highway project arrived just as Eatonville’s most famous daughter found the ramp lights again.
The former neighbors of the Hurstons now considered her a savior.
To show what could happen to its highway, the community began planning the Hurston Festival in 1988.
Thousands of fans arrived at the inaugural event two years later, and every January many return for the celebration.
After several years, the state withdrew from the highway proposal.
"The five currents of the highway have resurrected, you would say directly detonated, a real civic pride," Nathiri said.
Boyd put it more simply: "Zora saved Eatonville."
Victory over the highway project helped change the image of the city.
Out-of-towners such as Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who began attending church here in 1993, began to appear in larger numbers, and residents began to reassess the past.
Eatonville joined the National Historic Register in 1998.
The new one-story library (named after Hurston, of course) opened in 2006 on the re-asphalted and beautified Kennedy Boulevard.
Today, Eatonville remains a Florida anomaly: just six miles from downtown Orlando, it can sometimes act as a sunken alley in the summer rain, as small as when it was founded with only 27 black families in the 1880s.
(He is now 90% black.)
Strangers who come to seek the story and meaning of Eatonville are still often treated with caution.
Permission for most interviews is required in advance, and certain things - such as murals in Eatonville's oldest church, which were painted by whites and which depict blacks in the fields - are not allowed to be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, like Jones, a bold, confident teacher who likes deep red, still fear that their isolated community will not be properly understood.
And just as the Hurston Festival has grown, so has domestic pride.
Especially young people tend to see Eatonville as Hurston saw her whole race: beautiful, with problems and all, but no better, no worse, and as proud, creative, hardworking, foolish, and diverse as other American races and ethnicities.
The voice of Franklin's nephew, 18-year-old Edwin Harvey, echoes a sincere love for the village as he plans to return to Eatonville after college to work in the local government or the police, which he says would use some help.
And even younger ones, such as the 11-year-old Winter Park twins Alondra and Alexia Kenon, seem to have learned to describe Eatonville correctly.
"Most people, when they just drive through here, think, 'Well, this town is nothing against the others,'" said Alondra Kenon recently after church.
"But if you really stop and look at history for a while, it's a very nice city."
Here in New York, we all speak fluent financial
At first glance, nothing has changed here.
If tourists in Manhattan stayed away from the newsstands and giant TV screens in Times Square, they wouldn’t realize they were standing in the middle of a storm.
They would never guess that in the glazed bee hive of offices above their heads, the bankers and investment fund managers who monopolize New York City each day have the worst "bad day in the office" since the 1929 crisis.
Messengers still rattle metal carts on sidewalks and carry muffin pancakes to breakfast meetings.
Hispanics still move between the towers and wear, like human mules, fifty ironed shirts that hang from the balances on their backs.
Office rats are still waiting in line for their morning bagel at street food stalls, and it's still not possible to get a yellow cab on a weekday between 4:00 and 7:00 p.m.
It didn’t look like a crisis at all until I decided, with all the talk of pessimism, to open a savings account on Thursday afternoon.
Even though I timed the task to coincide with the late afternoon siesta at my local JP Morgan Chase branch, there were already about twenty people waiting in line there.
Not in front of the cashier's windows to pick up or store cash, but in front of the counter where older clients order checkbooks, tourists ask for directions to the Macy's convenience store, and new customers set up accounts.
Most of the people before me, as I learned from Starr, my "licensed personal banker," came for the same reason I did.
However, compared to me, they have already withdrawn their savings from smaller banks in places where they came from, such as New Jersey, Pennsylvania or Staten Island.
They collected money from so-called thrifts (a bit like building societies), money unions and those types of savings banks whose branches operate only in one state and which claim to take care of their customers as a family.
In the past year, 15 such banks have quietly collapsed.
A few days ago, Washington Mutual, a bank with $327 billion in assets, went bankrupt, and as the New Yorkers were returning home for the weekend on Friday night, another bank, Wachovia, with $440 billion in assets, was trying to catch a rescue buyer.
The office and shop workers who stood in front of me, fearing another collapse, were moving their cash to a bank that is seen as a safe haven and that does most of the rescue on Wall Street.
Ordinary New Yorkers have learned to be fluent in finance over the past week.
A woman in my local Chinese supermarket spoke on the phone and spoke to Lehman Borthers, the bankrupt bank, and her emaciated chief executive Dick Fuld with such familiarity as if she were gossiping about a lazy colleague.
And Lyn, the uniformed housekeeper of my apartment building, about 50 years old, changed the subject of our usual conversation - Brad, Angelina or my grocery delivery.
After my visit to the bank, she told me, "I now have my savings in money market funds.
I've moved it, I won't risk it."
Muslim graves desecrated after Austrian right-wing break
Heinz-Christian Strache, on the left, from the Austrian right-wing Freedom Party and Filip Dewinter from the Belgian right-wing party Vlaams Belang attend a demonstration that presented in Antwerp on Thursday 17 January 2008 the organization "Cities Against Islamization".
They carry signs similar to traffic signs that depict mosques crossed with a red line.
Police accuse right-wing extremists of desecrating a Muslim cemetery in Austria on the same weekend in which extreme-right parties made huge gains in the general election.
More than 90 graves in the cemetery in Traun near Linz were badly damaged sometime between Friday evening and this morning, and police believe it was an organized event.
The perpetrators spray-painted Jewish symbols on some graves, such as the Star of David, but detectives believe it may have been an attempt to mask the motives of extremists led by hatred of Muslim immigrants.
It is unclear whether the incident was connected to the election.
A spokesman for the Islamic community said they were "deeply shocked" by reports of desecration as the Muslim month of Ramadan draws to a close.
Meanwhile, Austria is entering a round of soul-searching after a right-wing slump in yesterday's parliamentary election.
Both far-right parties, which together won more than 30 percent of the vote, the Freedom Party and the Union for the Future of Austria, waged a vehemently anti-immigration campaign, and some of their slogans were condemned by critics as xenophobic.
Heinz-Christian Strache, the leader of the Freedom Party, which won more than 18 percent of the vote, campaigned against headscarves and burqas, and even expressed his opposition to meals that are perceived to be related to Islam.
At his last meeting with voters in Vienna, he spoke of a "European brotherhood" to prevent the rise of Islam.
Both sides are trying to ban the construction of mosques and minarets, arguing that they are political symbols of the ongoing Islamization of Austria and Europe.
Surveys and analyses carried out immediately after the elections, which put the extreme right in the position of the strongest political bloc in the country, indicate that this change was mainly caused by young voters who are worried about their future in the European Union.
Gary Glitter is not allowed to travel abroad
Gary Glitter, a glamrock star who has been convicted of child sexual abuse, has been banned from travelling to France and Spain.
Officials imposed the six-month ban on Glitter after he informed monitoring authorities that he planned to travel via France to Spain.
Kent police approved the travel ban last Thursday after handing over evidence of Glitter's past convictions for child sexual abuse to officials.
Glitter, real name Paul Gadd, did not attend the hearing at the Ashford Lowest Criminal Court in Kent, but was represented by lawyers from Corker Binning.
A spokesman for the court service said: "On Thursday 25 September, in Ashford's lowest criminal court, Kent police asked for a regulation to prevent Mr Paul Gadda from crossing the border into France and Spain until 25 March.
Paul Gadd did not attend personally."
Glitter, 64, has informed authorities that he wishes to travel abroad as required by his sex offender record.
He must notify the authorities if he wants to travel abroad for more than three days.
They must also give the planned departure date to the police a week in advance.
If he fails to inform the authorities, he could be sentenced to five years.
Kent police announced they would not discuss individual cases of Glitter's possible trips around the county.
A spokesperson for Kent Police said: "Kent Police will do everything necessary to protect children in this country or abroad.
From our point of view, it is easier to watch someone stay in the UK because we have extensive systems that handle potential dangers more effectively.
“Protecting Kent residents is a top priority for Kent police, and we are working hard to monitor the behavior of recorded sex offenders to minimise any danger to the public.”
Glitter returned to the UK last month after spending 27 months in a Vietnamese prison for the abuse of two girls aged 10 and 11.
When he was released, he flew to Bangkok, where he was scheduled to board a flight to London.
But he said he wasn't feeling well, and refused to fly to London.
Thai authorities did not let him pass passport control and he eventually flew to Hong Kong.
Chinese authorities also refused to allow him to enter and he flew back to Bangkok, where Thai police and immigration officials insisted on his return to Britain.
On 22 August, he finally arrived at Heathrow Terminal 3 and stayed there while his attorney David Corker went to Uxbridge's lowest criminal court in West London and at the same time Scotland Yard successfully requested an order ordering him to register as a sex offender.
Glitter was previously jailed in the UK for four months for possessing child pornography.
A Interior Ministry source said that Jacqui Smith, the Home Secretary, was calm and glad that Glitter had been prevented from traveling to France and Spain.
"To capture the true character, I take pictures of the master off-stage."
No heels, no frills, no costumes.
Only the essences of the great flamenco masters, detached from the focus on interpretation - only then will I achieve the relaxed expression of a man or a woman.
On the one hand, an artist.
On the other - a man.
Inseparable, apart from privacy, in those moments far from the audience - then you can see a confidential gesture, the depth of a glance or a passionate gesticulation of hands that are carefree because they are not going to get on the scene.
In "Flamenco-people", the German Gunther Bauer alternates the theatricality of performances with singers, dancers and guitarists with the lesser-known face of the masters.
With this intention, the photographer creates a unique iconography of flamenco from different environments.
The exhibition, which takes place as part of the Months of Flamenco Photography (Mes de la Fotografía Flamenca) program, "reflects the ever-increasing international importance of flamenco", says the author, explaining that "Flamenco-people" "can be any people, but when you look at the photographs, you find that these are not typical pictures of artists on the scene.
These people portrayed "on the street" are artists able to bring passion, sadness, joy to the scene... and completely captivate the audience.
To capture the personality of these artists, it is not necessary to take pictures on stage.
He carries his personality and character inside.
I was interested in creating a relaxed atmosphere that will allow me to capture the personality of the flamenco giants.
Enchanted by the "Cante de las Minas" festival, Bauer began a long journey of portraying flamenco singers, guitarists, and dancers on a board camera in 1997.
They are portraits that, thanks to the choice of camera and material, resemble classic photography.
Applying different stylistic means is at odds with the classical basis of the film and gives it a contemporary spirit, an idea that, according to Bauer himself, also mirrors flamenco: "Music with very traditional roots, but which does not cease to surprise and develop."
What draws the audience away is not the action of the dance, singing or playing itself, but the personality and character of the artist.
The search for the moment when we meet the most essential, the spirit that manifests itself in the way of perception, being and experiencing, was and is the constant of the work presented during these days in the gallery El Fotómata.
This selection of nearly seventy photographed artists is shaped by well-known flamenco characters such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Moreente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales and Vicente Amigo.
The project has become a kind of anthology of flamenco and soon there will be a book edition that will contain exhibited portraits.
A passion for portraiture led Bauer two years ago to the idea of repeating it on "Portraits of Sports Veteran" ("SportARTproject").
Although their concept is different from "Flamenco-people", the photographer admits that "taking pictures of people, getting to know them and being able to enter their lives for a while, whether for a long time or just a short one - that's my passion.
I think that in photography, portrait is the most difficult genre.
A person meets or clashes with people, personalities they sometimes do not even know, or they give him a few minutes to take pictures.
Despite similar circumstances, as a photographer I always try to realize my ideas."
A collection of contemporary flamenco portraits entitled "Flamenco-people" is on display at the Galeria El Fotómata in 20 de la Mata street, parallel to Alameda de Hércules, and can be visited until 16 October.
