Talking in sleep
Some kids talk at night.
I don’t mean those who wake up and tell us something that happened the day before, but children who talk while they sleep.
When it happens for the first time, it may scare you, but it’s actually meaningless.
This is a harmless sleep disorder called somniloquy.
It is quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
I'm sure some of you have been told that he spoke in his sleep at night.
This phenomenon can occur very sporadically (for example, once in a lifetime with high fevers), or with greater regularity (every day, once a week, once every few months...), the next day the child does not remember anything.
There is no single reason to explain his arrival.
It is often associated with other sleep disorders, such as nightmares, night terrors, enuresis nocturna, or sleepwalking, but it doesn’t have to be.
As mentioned earlier, it can often be accompanied by very high fevers, stress or flare-ups.
In any case, this is a little studied phenomenon.
The intensity with which it appears is also different.
The child can speak in a calm voice, say individual words, whisper, or just the opposite (screaming, crying, long speeches...).
In cases where it manifests itself with great force, it would be advisable to observe the child and consult a specialist to see if he has any problem that causes him great anxiety and in this way he manifests himself.
We have said that it is a harmless disorder, so it is not treated only if it is associated with another sleep disorder that can be treated (for example, if it is associated with apnea syndrome or with permanent stress).
However, we can do this by keeping in mind a few very simple preventive measures, such as:
Try not to upset the baby too much before going to bed.
So look for quiet games and avoid scary or somewhat violent TV programs or series.
For very nervous children and those who can relax, it is possible to use relaxation techniques that will help them get some inner peace.
This will allow the child to sleep more peacefully.
When somniloquy appears, try to remain calm.
Remind yourself that it is harmless to the child and that he will not remember anything from what happened the next day.
Helpful advice
Don't be him.
It is useless because he is not conscious and you interrupt his sleep.
Even when he speaks, he sleeps, and therefore he rests.
Keep in mind that if you find yourself feeling very distressed several times in a row, it would be helpful to seek advice or find out what is causing such anxiety in your child.
If there is an understanding of what he is saying (which is not so common), avoid the temptation to question him and draw information from him.
It won't do any good, because when he's asleep, he's not conscious enough to organize his thoughts.
In addition, you will hear what he says, but you do not know what he is dreaming about, and therefore why he is saying it, so be very careful how you interpret information and what conclusions you come to.
Never tell a child that you can ask them their secret at night.
