Interview - Blood, which again is certain
Héma-Québec celebrated its tenth anniversary yesterday and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, was right to rejoice as Héma-Québec became one of the most reliable and efficient blood suppliers in the world.
Above all, he regained the trust of the public, who were severely shaken after the Contaminated Blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is well known, the state blood reserve administered by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Department was contaminated with the Immune Deficiency Virus (HIV) and the Hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
Because of this drama and a wave of public outrage, the Canadian government launched a public inquiry in February 1994, chaired by Judge Horace Krever, to explain the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to formulate a recommendation not to repeat such a disaster.
While Judge Krever lingered in handing over the report, some provinces set up a committee to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélinea Committee took up this role.
Following the Gélineau and Krever reports, two suppliers were established in Canada: Hema-Québec, which was to manage Québec, and the Canadian Blood Society to supply all provinces and both territories.
“When Héma-Québec began its activities in 1998, barely 38% of people still had confidence in Quebec’s blood system,” says Dr. Décary.
"The situation was disheartening.
By continuously working to increase the safety of blood products and by constantly working in this area over the years, we have regained public trust," he says, adding proudly that by the beginning of 2008 almost 94% of the Quebec population had already trusted Hema-Quebek.
Dr. Décary, however, does not lose sight of the fact that "trust is something very fragile".
Since its establishment on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
"At that time, we saw many cases of the human form of mad cow disease, a new variant of the disease called Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease in Europe," says a woman who has led the company since it was founded in 1998.
“We didn’t know if this disease could spread through the blood.
Therefore, we relied on one of the basic recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports, according to which when we do not know and when a serious disease is at stake, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is characterized by brain degeneration inevitably leading to death, we need to take exclusionary measures.
Thus, in April 1999, we rejected blood from people who had been in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
A few years ago, it was safely proven that this disease is transmitted through the blood.
So this episode showed us that adhering to the precautionary principle made sense."
In 1999, a much more accurate technique for detecting HIV appeared on the market: tests using nucleic acid (NAT), which allow to detect in the donor blood the presence of the virus itself, and not the presence of antibodies, on which the tests used previously were based.
NAT tests have made it possible to shorten the period of deafness that occurs between the moment of infection of the patient and the moment when the first viruses can be detected by our techniques in the blood, the specialist explains.
We were able to shorten this period to less than a week.
We significantly reduced the risk that some donors might be infected without knowing it and without being able to figure it out.
These improvements have made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of getting AIDS through blood transfusions.
One in 12 million people today is at risk of getting blood contaminated with HIV.
In other words, it means that 12 million blood products will need to be distributed before someone can become infected with HIV.
Since Hema-Québec distributes 400,000 to 500,000 blood products each year, it will take 24 years for the first case of HIV transmission through a blood product to occur.
I believe that today we can safely get or prescribe a blood transfusion necessary for healing," said Hema-Quebek.
“The challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
We never know what kind of germs may appear in the system.
Just last year, the chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted to the blood by insect stings.
We need to be vigilant at all times,” continues Dr. Décary, stressing that in addition to a safe supply, Hema-Québec must also count on a sufficient supply.
“The needs are growing as the population ages.
As a result of more aggressive treatment of cancer, patients often need a new dose of red blood cells or platelets.
The aging population also has implications for the blood donor network, which on average consists of only 3% of Québecs allowed to donate."
Every healthy person is at least 18 years old, according to the criteria of admissibility, but can donate blood only once every 56 days, that is, six times a year.
On average, 14% of blood donors are not accepted because they are carriers of AIDS or malaria, and if they have visited a country where mud fever is rampant, they are excluded for one year.
"With this 3%, we can maintain a state that meets the needs of hospitals.
Deficiencies are very rare.
However, members of the donor network need to be replenished in proportion to how they age and can no longer donate blood.
However, persuading people to give blood is difficult, especially keeping them and encouraging them to become regular donors.
“Life is so unfettered today that we rarely find an hour to donate blood,” said Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Québec supplies not only blood products, but also human tissue such as bone transplants, heart valves, eyeballs, and skin that is almost exclusively used for major burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being deposited with Hema-Québek, who also administers the only public cord blood bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord, previously thought to be biomedical waste, is rich in stem-cell-rich blood that can be used to treat serious diseases such as leukemia.
“A few weeks ago, we celebrated the deposit of our 1,000th cord blood sample into the bank, and we expect to take over 1,000 of them a year.
At the beginning of next year, we should start offering them for transplants," explains Dr. Décary, who describes the cord blood collection program as very popular.
"Some mothers are disappointed that they do not have access to it," because Hema-Québec does not have enough resources to offer this complex and expensive program to all hospitals in Quebec.
