Opinions - Barrick Gold's Orwellian Discourse
In the September 17 issue, Le Devoir published a letter by Patrick J. Garver, executive vice president of the Canadian mining company Barrick Gold.
With Orwellian logic, he confirms that the world's largest gold producer has launched a prosecution of three authors and a poor little publishing house for libel in order to spark a "transparent public debate" and demands six million from them.
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, they do not judge the truth, especially in the case of an affront to honor, but the law.
Unsurprisingly, Garver completely ignores this crucial distinction.
Or is the best way for Barrick Gold to hold a public debate is to bankrupt anyone who dares to defend the opposite position?
Whatever the outcome of the trial, the authors and publisher of Noir Canada will be forced to spend respectable sums of money in order to be ready to defend themselves and fight in a very unbalanced fight against the army of lawyers supported by the almost bottomless pockets of the mining company.
The tactic in these unbalanced fights, after all, often consists in bankrupting the defendants in order to enforce conciliation, which will clog the mouths of the opposing party and, moreover, frighten anyone who would dare to devote himself to this matter.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it should have presented its view of the whole thing to the public.
Contrary to what is happening in several of the countries where Barrick Gold operates, in Canada the debate normally lies in the exchange of ideas and not in the blows with a baton.
Mining companies, therefore, were not enough to open up their books, their documentation, and to initiate a real debate through newspapers, media, publications, and funding of independent scientific teams that could shed light on the matter.
Barrick Gold, however, seems to have no confidence in public opinion, and has vehemently rejected petitions and letters in support of the authors of Noir Canada.
Perhaps Garver could explain how he can demand a "public debate", while simultaneously disdaining the views of the same public?
It seems that this word in the vice president's world only refers to boldly paid attorneys, and not all Canadians; this is a rather narrow concept of the term.
In a democracy, even detractors have the right to speak out.
Barrick Gold doesn't understand - or doesn't want to understand - that the public who support the authors and publishers of Noir Canada does so primarily because they reject the brutal ways of the mining company.
The public is prepared to question Barrick and assess the matter, but based on a civilized exchange of arguments, not within what many perceive as a prosecution in which the defendant's mouth is to be shut (as part of its prosecution of the "public debate", by the way, Barrick has just filed an official appeal to the authors of Noir Canada to officially announce that they are to stop using the term...).
Aside from Garver’s surreal speech, Barrick Gold’s prosecution is a direct assault on the university’s freedom to explore and seek the truth that is essential to any democratic society.
Overall, it denies the right to quote credible sources and to debate facts and interpretations that constitute the very basis of intellectual activity.
If, in a country like Canada, it is impossible to study and discuss topics that the rich companies of this world do not like, without exposing themselves to repeated prosecution, who else will be able to do it?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, it could have formed it if it followed the scientific standards used by the authors of Noir Canada.
He's entitled to an answer.
The university environment to which we belong has long been able to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold’s exaggerated lawsuit makes it clear that despite what it claims, it has not the slightest desire to have a transparent debate.
This is a loss for the university world, as it is for public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to put in place measures to limit this type of unwarranted prosecution.
Operation to Save Wall Street - Democrats and Republicans Understand Each Other
The Bush administration and congressional leaders, both Republicans and Democrats, finally reached an agreement on the largest economic rescue plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
A new version of the $700 billion plan to stem the financial crisis that has been plaguing Wall Street for months has yet to be approved by both houses of Congress.
In particular, it assumes: better control of elected representatives over its application, new mechanisms to ensure the repayment of deposited public money, new measures to capture the number of houses seized due to non-payment, as well as the right to monitor the amount of wages paid to managers of rescued companies.
U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, House Speaker Nancy Pelosi, and Republican Representative at the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced this good news yesterday a few minutes after midnight, after the conclusion of the two-day negotiating marathon.
"We have made great progress and have reached an agreement that is effective in the markets," Bush administration official Henry Paulson said in a statement.
“Everything has been done to keep the real economy and ordinary Americans safe from the ongoing Wall Street crisis,” he said.
“This is a crucial point: if we don’t, the trauma, chaos, and disruption to Americans’ daily lives will be enormous,” Gregg said.
Over the last few hours, negotiations have taken off for fear of the effect that another failure would have on investors’ minds.
The time limit was to open the markets this morning.
Both candidates for the US presidency were invited to negotiate later, and both spoke out in favor of the deal rather than neglecting to express their displeasure at the need to resort to such an extreme solution.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama credited the agreement with some measures, especially one aimed at allowing owners to keep their residence, and measures on the salary of the heads of state-sponsored companies.
"When we ask taxpayers to take special measures because of the irresponsibility of some people, there is nothing to congratulate ourselves on.
But these measures are necessary," he explained on the TV waves.
His Republican opponent John McCain, who was asked by another station if he would vote for the proposed plan, replied, "I'd like to see the details, but I hope so."
"The rough features that I have read [show] that this is something that we will all have to spend and with which it will be possible to move forward.
It is simply unacceptable to choose inaction," he said.
The goal of the $700 billion plan is to buy back dubious receivables and risky and unsold assets of U.S. financial institutions with taxpayer money.
The plan comes after a 14-month crisis unleashed by the bursting housing bubble that first led to the collapse of subprimes, then passed on to other, more widespread forms of lending (PCAAs) and resulted in cash freezes and the breakdown of banks and financial institutions.
The fall of the first draft agreement last week was the fault of Republican MPs.
Ever since the Democrats agreed that some of the "toxic" assets of companies in difficulty would only be guaranteed by the government, but would not buy them back, there is a belief that the impasse is over.
In an effort to reconcile conflicting views in Congress, provision was made for the government to be able to introduce new fees to help it recover its deposit if, as a result of the program, it had to take losses over a period of five years.
The new plan includes a first deposit of $250 billion, to which an additional $100 billion can be added if the president deems it necessary.
A further $350 billion is expected to be approved by Congress in a new vote.
In exchange for its assistance, Washington will acquire shares in the rescued companies, which will pay dividends to it in case of profit, and which it will be able to resell when it is over.
The federal government will be able to delay the confiscation procedures related to the loans covered by the plan, as well as set limits on the amount of remuneration and compensation paid to executives of affected companies.
The drafters would like to put it to a vote in the House of Representatives today and in the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all efforts, it is not yet certain whether their plan will have the green light.
Yesterday, voices continued to rise against the project in both the Republican and Democratic camps.
"It's perfectly obvious that Washington can't hear you," House Finance Committee member Scott Garrett said.
“We have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But making money from taxpayers is not the solution."
Democratic Rep. Brad Sherman, the moderator of a group of congressmen nicknamed the "Skeptics Committee," presents the whole thing differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
"Four hundred distinguished economics professors, among them three Nobel Prize winners, have written to us: we ask Congress not to rush too much and to carefully examine which path to take," he said.
At the same time, it has been reaffirmed in Europe that this crisis is a global crisis.
Following the end of the extraordinary meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalisation of the Fortis banking group for EUR 11.2 billion (USD 16.3 billion).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg became necessary after French bank BNP Paribas announced that it was withdrawing from the purchase of its competitor, which has been on the verge of collapse since losing 2 billion euros ($2.9 billion) due to the crisis of risky loans to buy real estate in the United States.
Fortis employs 85,000 people, ranks among Europe’s top 20 banks and among Europe’s top ten insurers.
"We will not lose this money," Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos said yesterday.
"In return, we gain the right to vote in the bank and influence.
And that is what savers and households can appreciate in these uncertain times.”
On the other side of the English Channel, the British government has begun nationalising another bank hit by the financial crisis.
According to the English press, the government was to take over all of Bradford and Bringley’s existing loans, of which more than 41 billion (US$75.5 billion) were real estate loans.
According to its announcement yesterday, branches and accounts of clients of the British bank will be bought by the Spanish bank Santander.
Bradford and Bringley will be the second bank after Northern Rock to be nationalised by the British government since the start of the financial crisis.
Paul Newman (1925-2008) - The Death of a Socially Engaged Icon
His beauty with azure eyes has long represented his trump card, according to others weakness.
Did this American actor break out of narcissism with a charming smile?
Yes and no.
The shyness, sensitivity, and unceasing talent that he possessed also distanced him from the power category that begets true stars.
But what a long-distance runner he was!
Paul Newman died Friday at the age of 83 at his Connecticut ranch as a result of lung cancer, and remains one of the last icons of the greasy years of American cinema.
Less grandiose than Brando, to whom he was similar and for a long time a sort of rival on the screen, Newman was a more cautious actor, certainly more fragile, but also an apostle of freedom and the breakdown of dramatic conventions.
Mixed blood often produces beautiful children.
Born in Ohio in 1925, his father was a German Jew and his mother was originally Hungarian.
From these European roots was born one of the famous faces of the American dream.
No over-ego, which is the last sign of quality.
Because in it, the whole country was in love with self-made man, a warrior in the Pacific War, wounded in battle, who in the early 1950s studied acting at Yale, then attended New York's Actor's Studio and celebrated triumph in theater, on television and soon in film.
The same man who fought for civil rights was also a race car driver who came second at the 1979 24 Hours of Le Mans and a sex symbol, despite being a model couple with actress Joanne Woodward since 1958.
With him also go the dark places of this hidden, discreet, socially engaged star, allergic to the fuss of his own show-business, which will forever remain mysterious to some extent.
A decent man, in the noblest sense of the word.
The departure of Paul Newman this weekend has caused a vertigo for film lovers, while his big roles rival each other on the black screen of memories.
It is followed by more than half a century of ever-changing American seventh art.
A charming cowboy from Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid (1969), a young man who rejects his sensual wife (Elizabeth Taylor) in Cat on a Hot Roof, a 1958 adaptation of Tennessee Williams, resurfaces in memory.
From a less distant past (1990), we recall his sensitive Mr. Bridge, troubled at an advanced age by a marriage that did not meet all expectations.
So many Paul Newmans have gone down in history.
Boxer Rocky Graziano, the battered, violent, unforgettable delinquent from Somebody Up There Likes Me by Robert Wise, a role intended for James Dean, taken after his death, which brought Newman into true familiarity in 1956.
A sympathetic gangster in the absolutely great The Sting, Academy Award for Best Picture in 1973.
A bitter and vengeful billiard player in Robert Rossen's The Hustler (1961), he will portray the same character in Martin Scorsese's The Color of Money, bringing him the only Oscar out of seven nominations in 1987.
This face that's been wandering for ages, it was him.
There he is again.
In his professional career, various epochs compete with each other.
The young know him mainly thanks to the cult Slap Shot by George Roy Hill (1977) from the role of Reggie Dunlop, an unconventional hockey coach.
Fans reunited with him in 1994 at The Hudsucker Proxy of the Coen Brothers.
He ended his career as the godfather of the Irish mafia in Road to Perdition by Sam Mendes in 2003.
Unlike a few movie legends that left the craft relatively soon, Newman remained in the business for a long time, though he denounced Hollywood with its tinsel, pomp, and concessions.
French filmmaker Bertrand Tavernier considered it, not without humor, "a living challenge of underplaying", judging that in his performances he pushed too hard.
For the beautiful Paul Newman, to whom the roles came as a tray, the profession was not always so tender.
However, he played the early lovers less often than the outsiders: neurotics, alcoholics, scoundrels and despairers, whose decadence and rebellion were reflected in his perfect features.
As a director, Newman revealed little-known aspects of his shy sensibilities.
His 1968 film Rachel, Rachel (based on the novel by Canadian Margaret Laurence), starring his wife Joanne Woodward, features a sensitive female portrait full of melancholy.
In 1984, he dedicated the film Harry and Son, a work of shame and sadness, to his son Scott, whom he had lost due to an overdose.
In a flurry of honors Newman received yesterday, his great friend and former teammate Robert Redford (played together in The Sting and Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid) sadly declared, "His presence has made my life and this country better."
Generosity, love of life, these are the main characteristics of the deceased actor.
Apart from his legendary career, there is also a great civil rights fighter, ecology, independent film, and an opponent of the decline of Hollywood.
We used to see his likeness on bottles of wine vinegar, sauces, biscuits and other foods, which may have seemed rather tasteless to us, although at first it was gag.
However, the profits from the sale went to the account of his Foundation for a Hard Childhood.
So rather than let himself be lulled by fame, Newman engaged in society until the very last moment.
He left his five daughters a letter containing these sentences: "Always and to the end, your father was grateful to his happy planet.
It was an honor to be here."
And for us, it was an honor to follow the path of such a clairvoyant and generous American artist.
And besides, after all, a model citizen.
What was produced in the invoice factory Zuschlag & spol.?
Soon, on October 8, the trial in criminal proceedings against János Zuschlag and his associates will begin.
In addition to other crimes, including forgery of documents, the politician and his associates are accused of fraud committed by a long-term and systematic criminal organization, as a result of which extremely significant damage was caused.
According to the prosecutor's office, they used the money obtained in public tenders for their own purposes and often documented the fulfillment of tasks with fictitious invoices.
Money from the state and local governments - a total of about 65 million forints - went partly to the treasury of the organization Fiatal Baloldal, partly to the pockets of individuals.
The method also reported by the investigating authority was that the money raised in public tenders was collected on the basis of invoices for which there was no actual consideration and the commitments were never received by the associations.
According to the prosecution, a large part of the invoices were fake.
Forms for these invoices came from the Józsefváros market, round stamps were made in Kiskunhalasi.
The names of the companies to which the invoices are to be produced were decided, among others, on a round trip along the northern shore of Lake Balaton, on which István Lados was sent by János Zuschlag.
According to his testimony, the first one was to look at guest houses and restaurants.
In them, he applied for bills for his consumption, according to the model of which invoices were then produced as part of public tenders published by, among others, the Ministry of Youth and Sport, the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs, or the Self-Government of the capital city.
Invoices were issued mostly by István Lados with his partner András Úri, who, according to our information, most often wrote the reports needed to obtain subsidies.
During his "study trip", Lados spotted one cellar.
According to two invoices issued by Zuschlag and its associates in 2003, this catering facility provided catering for a 90-member group from the Biztos Pont association.
However, according to the company manager, so many people would not fit into this device at once.
Similarly, the invoice issued in the summer of 2002 to a foundation called Jobb Juvért, later Egyutt and Harmadik Vezredért, was teeming with formal and content errors.
The guest house in Badacsonytomaj had only three rooms, more than ten people could not sleep in it one evening, yet there were 130 guests on the invoice.
Fillers of forms with a rich imagination, however, exaggerated this even when they mentioned on the documents a company dedicated also to hospitality - Pigal s. r. o., in whose accounting according to the information provided to the Public Prosecutor's Office the documents bearing the names Jobb Juvért and Hoppa were not even included.
The head of the company, Gyoz Farkas, told hvg.hu that when he was summoned to the prosecutor's office and shown invoices, he immediately knew that these were false documents.
"The name of our business and our tax number were in the wrong place on the stamp."
He added that apart from the formalities, they did not agree that they had accommodated 100 people according to the invoice, as they only have eleven rooms that do not have such a large capacity.
In addition, the invoice also included meals, and their restaurant has not worked for a long time.
Zealous invoice producers did not convince themselves that the sought-after Budapest travel agency only organizes foreign trips, and they foolishly referred to the invoice with cash payment, which also did not coincide with the company’s billing practice, as a service of arranging a trip around Hungary.
In addition, VAT was also included in the document, as revealed in the course of the investigation, although the organisation of trips to countries outside the European Union was exempt from VAT.
The four documents issued by Hotel Révf -l -p s. r. o. to the Jobb J -vért Foundation did not agree on the amount of VAT. The company's activity is not subject to the 25 percent VAT, but to the 15 percent VAT, in addition, the hotel employees issued only printed invoices, but the invoice was hand-written.
In addition, the "issuers" spoiled the invoice, for example, by stating at one company, as it turned out thanks to the investigation of the prosecutor's office, as the activity of road transport of goods, which the company based originally on investment advice did not carry out.
Moreover, the fact that the invoices issued by the Egyutt Foundation and the Harmadik Zezredért and the XXI Századi Kulturális Egyesélet and Biztos Pont associations are false was also revealed due to formal deviations - an incorrect invoice format and a false stamp.
As in the case of Ravenna k. s. or the Sporting Camp in Kunfehértó, whose representatives denied that they would issue invoices.
For example, the counterfeiters did not notice that the company HIB s. r. o. from Nyíregyháza was in liquidation at the time (2001), when it was fed by a group from the Fiatal Városért association, which is why, according to our information, the liquidation commissioner of the company also denied that he had issued the paper.
Invoices were issued consciously
The second group of invoicers are those who knew to issue a fictitious invoice.
The Esély Budapestért Foundation has issued accounts for approximately four million forints for the Harmadik ’vezredért Foundation at the request of the organization Fiatal Baloldal - Ifjú Szocialisták.
According to the indictment, the head of Collab s. r. o. was forced to issue a fictitious account by one of the defendants, Ludovic Gy-rfi.
The company Biogate s.r.o. also cooperated with Zuschlag and its associates, currently in liquidation, which in 2003 supplied Jobb J-v-ért and the Atlasz and V-r-sfeny associations with invoices worth approximately five million forints, which were not supported by actual economic activity.
Nor the movement of money, because the created invoices were later canceled, which, of course, the organizations forgot to mention in their documents.
Another group of invoicing companies includes those that had ties to the defendants.
Thus, for example, Iván Kubatov was appointed representative of the Ukrainian representative of Delta Trió s.r.o., a company dealing in fuel and motor vehicles, based in Budapest, where the company is not located.
The company issued several invoices in October, November and December 2005 for the sale of computer equipment worth approximately 18 million forints.
According to the data established by the investigation, these invoices were purchased by Kiskunhalas Cash Investment s. r. o., which had been in liquidation since 14 September 2005.
The managing director of this company was a man from Romania, to whom Iván Kubatov was supposed to hand over documents related to the company in 2002-2005.
As we know, Kubatov admitted during the investigation that he issued invoices on behalf of the company to the associations Atlasz, Hoppa and the Egyutt Foundation and Harmadik'vezredért, and he himself accepted their consideration.
At the request of Iván Kubatov, the companies Fa-Bani Jos Faipari s. r. o. and Jos-Investment k. s. were founded by Romanian masons.
In fact, none of the companies worked, according to the defendant, because they did not get a job.
Nevertheless, the companies benefited him by issuing invoices on behalf of the companies to the associations Atlasz and Y-Generáció connected to Zuschlag at the request of the co-defendant Zsolt Szente, who also prepared their instruments of incorporation.
On behalf of Investment, Delta Trió, Fa-Bani Jos, Jos Investment and Linaxtrade, Kubatov has given organizations a total of 15 invoices worth 14.2 million forints.
The prosecutor's office concluded that Kubatov had lost 10 percent of the amounts indicated on invoices and VAT.
To issue fictitious invoices, this time for a tender for the Biztos Pont association, the man also used the company Szi-Beri k. t.
In January 2006, the associations Y-Generáció and Sz-vetség and Modern Magyarországért submitted proposals to the public tender of the Mihálye Táncsics Foundation (TMA), a public benefit organization of the Socialist Party.
They received 500,000 forints each, but did not spend the money on the goals outlined in the proposals.
In order not to reveal this, TMA submitted five fictitious invoices from Works Team s. r. o.
These invoices were found during a house search in the office of Árpád Kemecsei at the Ministry of Education.
During the trial, some of the defendants will probably describe the course of the production of invoices, as they have already done at the prosecutor’s office.
It may be more interesting if the main defendant, János Zuschlag, decides to reveal everything.
His testimony so far is not very detailed, and although he has promised to explain everything in detail several times, he has not done so yet.
The question is whether it is in his interest - in exchange for paying a large part of the damage, fifty million forints, with whom the socialists may have made a deal and Zusi will take it upon himself.
He could have been offended, because his requests for easing the conditions of his detention, i.e. for placing him under house arrest, had not yet been heard.
While the perpetrators of economic crimes, who have done much more damage than they have yet to pay, can walk freely or at least wait for the end of the proceedings against them in their homes, he does not have this option.
The psychology of trumping: why do we spend more money?
At auctions, customers are willing to spend more money, overestimate the goods.
The neurological and economic underpinnings of this familiar - and seemingly irrational - behavior have been revealed to researchers in the field of neurology and economics at New York University.
According to their study, published in the journal Science, people do not want to lag behind in the eBay auction competition, so they prefer to pay too high a price.
Through an experimental auction, the research attempted to map the scheme of this "game" in the nervous system.
One group of volunteers was betting, the other group participated in a live auction, using the functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) method to examine the active brain areas of the subjects.
In both games, participants could win money, but when playing at an auction, an important element of which is to trump the other side, the whole under the cerebral cortex, called the striatum, began to work intensively when losing.
This brain region, in addition to many other functions, plays a role in the "self-rewarding" mechanism of the nervous system.
Therefore, according to the researchers, screwing up the price can be explained by an attempt to avoid a sharp reaction of the striatum.
To support their theory, members of the research team from among economists conducted a cross-sectional financial survey.
There were three groups bidding against one partner under different conditions.
The control group was simply told what the real value of the product was, and they made bets.
In addition, members of the other group were promised that if they came out of the game victorious, they would receive an additional $15 as a reward.
The third group received $15 before the auction, but in the event of a loss, its members also lost this money.
The difference between the two groups, therefore, was that one was highlighted as a win and the other as a loss.
However, members of the group playing "against defeat" were willing to go higher than it was in the control and "winning" group, which confirms the hypothesis of neurologists.
"These results cannot be deduced from any pre-existing economic theory.
Until now, they have explained phenomena observable during auctions of the joys of victory and avoidance of risk.
It was neurological imaging methods that helped us resolve the contradiction between the two theories so that we now arrive at a third explanation," said Andrew Schotter, professor of economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: when to see a doctor?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C infection, and in Hungary, chronic liver disease is one of the leading causes of death.
The number of domestic cases of hepatitis infection is estimated at one hundred thousand, but only seven thousand of them are treated. The reason for this is that the sick often do not know that they are infected.
The name hepatitis is a collective term for infectious liver damage caused by various viruses.
There are many similarities in their symptoms, including inflammation of the liver and jaundice, but the causes of the disease and the diseases caused by them differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses spread in two main ways depending on the causative agents of the disease: hepatitis A and E by the digestive tract (for example, infected with food, water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses by blood and body fluids (sperm, vaginal secretions, saliva).
In any case, travelers should protect themselves by vaccination against virus A and B, against virus C the vaccine does not exist.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after eating an infected food, usually accompanied by nausea, weakness, abdominal discomfort, urge to vomit.
After that, jaundice forms on the skin and eye whites, lightened stools and darkens the urine. Treatment can take up to two to three weeks.
Every year, one million people worldwide die from a more serious type of the disease, liver cancer and liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main reason is that, according to estimates, only one in ten infected people is treated medically.
Also, hepatitis C can have very serious consequences: if not treated, it can lead to liver cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most people who are infected do not even know about their disease, the causative agent of the disease destroys liver cells maliciously, and so the first symptoms appear in many cases in 20-30 years.
Therefore, timely prevention, the implementation of regular writing is very important.
In three groups, the disease occurs much more often than on average: among people who underwent a blood transfusion before 1991, among drug users, and among people with tattoos.
Currently, the estimated worldwide number of individuals infected with the chronic hepatitis C virus is 200 million.
Since the disease can be demonstrated by a routine laboratory examination, a person should contact his general practitioner if he notices any symptom of unknown origin.
When detected early, the disease is curable, the virus can be removed from the body to prevent infection and prevent cancer.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, which was first organized by organizations representing the sick worldwide in 2004.
Its aim is to draw attention to the chronic inflammation of the liver caused by these viruses, the causes of its occurrence and the importance of early recognition of the disease.
If you believe in God, doesn’t it hurt so much?
According to recent research, belief in God functions as an analgesic that may have eased the death of Catholic martyrs.
Researchers at the University of Oxford have conducted an interesting experiment to study how belief in the god of pain affects a person, the Telegraph reported.
As part of a rather bizarre survey, 12 Catholic believers and an equal number of atheists were subjected to electric shocks, while everyone observed a painting depicting the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to eliminate much of the pain.
Thanks to a technique that examined the human brain in detail, it turned out that Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain that is responsible for regulating pain.
The research is the first in a series of studies involving academics, scientists, philosophers and theologians from different parts of the university.
Precisely, the test was performed by attaching a sparking instrument to the left hand of the subject, which emitted electric shocks.
The researchers asked the participants to observe two paintings: Sassoferrat’s Virgin Mary from the 17th century and Leonardo da Vinci’s Lady with an anteater, painted in the 15th century.
The authors of the research hoped that the view of the Virgin Mary would evoke a certain state of piety in the faithful, while the da Vinci image was chosen because it does not differ much from the first and gives them a calming impression.
The subjects spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, and during this time they received 20 electroshocks in four consecutive parts, while watching a religious or general-themed image separately.
Catholics reported that they felt "safe" when they looked at the Virgin Mary, as if they were "taken care of" and "calm down, filled with peace."
They felt 12 percent less pain when they saw a religious painting than when they saw Leonardo’s work.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who also participated in the research, believes that a similar effect can be achieved by using any strongly impressive image even among atheists, only the right photo needs to be found.
"We would have to find a picture that would be perceived very positively, from the position of mother or father," the psychologist said.
Anglican Bishop Tom Wright welcomed the results of the research.
“The practice of faith should change, and in many cases it will also change our personality,” Wright said.
After such great results, it is only a question of what effect it would have on the regulation of the pain of believers if they showed them some Madonna from Leonardo or a painter of a similar caliber.
Would looking at a quality Virgin Mary mean achieving even better results?
You are what you share
On their tenth birthday, Google can say that people can find it in their pocket at least as well as they can in the sky; they know where they’ve been on vacation, what examinations they’re taking, and what interests them.
However, according to Eric Schmidt, one of the company’s chief executives, this is still not enough.
But when it comes to skeptics paralleling Orwell’s dark vision, the very nature of Web 2.0 is not clear to them.
Eric Schmidt recently told the Financial Times that Google’s main goal is to collect even more personal data about users, which is necessary to enable Google’s founders to stick to their original intention, which was: “Let’s organize all the information in the world!”
According to Google, even after 10 years of world-class work, the company is just at the beginning of being able to work with all the information.
When asked what it would be like in five years' time, Schmidt replied that he would like Google to be able to answer questions such as "what should I do tomorrow?" or "what kind of work would actually be useful for me?" - but software won't be able to answer such seemingly simple questions until it knows enough about users.
Not all Internet users know that during an Internet search, the search words are accurately captured, as well as from which IP address they were searched and to which pages the interested parties moved after the search.
Thanks to the Personalized Search service launched two years ago, users can, for example, keep track of their surfing history, can look back at what they have searched for and clicked on, thanks to which, in the long term, they can generate findings tailored to them - the same logic will be based on the Recommendations service, through which the system will offer us products and services based on the previously mentioned and retained preferences.
“What if my data is used against me, what if someone looks at what I’m doing?” asked users who are worried about Google’s data monopoly.
In most cases, the extent of potential power represented by the company is frightening, the counter-reaction does not cause guilt, fear of punishment, desire for freedom or even a rebellion against power in Internet users.
However, it is a confirmed fact that all search terms are not only captured, but in justified cases they can also be issued to a third party, in such legal cases the personality rights of Internet users do not protect anything.
The most famous example recently was probably a coordinated action against Brazilian pedophiles, during which Google provided the Brazilian government with information that allowed the identification of pedophiles from the Orkut community sites established through it.
But Internet users worried about personality rights may have taken a breather in May when the firm and the EFF e-rights organization successfully proved their point in a dispute with the FBI: Google must not be forced by any article of the Constitution to provide any information secretly requested by the FBI.
(At the same time, the federal government successfully fought off nearly fifty thousand web addresses and a thousand search terms, which it obtained in reference to the strengthening of the adopted law on the protection of children years ago, yet it failed to get lists of search items of individual users, respectively, complete lists of websites and keywords covering a period of two months.)
The opinion about Google is quite contradictory: it is whipped by those who are afraid to provide their personal data, because they feel that their intimate sphere and private life will be, by starting to use Google services, exposed to harm, and they stand against it with a revolt, which belongs to multinational companies with a conservative image.
Meanwhile, American geek culture and its wild offshoot, amassing enthusiastic computer fans, activists, and users, appearing in many countries, sees it as a new generation of big business, a “corporation that’s on the move,” as opposed to its rival, Microsoft, who is seen as the world’s conquerors because of Windows, even though they both fight for the same goals.
This may be due to the fact that Google, unlike Microsoft, does not require an identification code from its users and does not want money for its applications; an open, free and constantly fresh source of information, and a package of programs acts as a much more accessible, youthful, "cooler" than the practice of an official software giant.
However, this may also be due to the fact that geeks accurately understand the very problematic relationship between the Internet and personality rights, which has brought with it just one of the most downgraded keywords of recent years: web 2.0.
Web 2.0 is about nothing more than cooperation, about deliberately leaving traces behind us and using the communication channels available to us, and although their scope is different for everyone, the essence remains the same: we show ourselves.
The average young person can have a profile on several community pages from Facebook to Xang, which can be easily linked to other services, such as Twitter or the last.fm app, recording the music he listens to, all this can then connect to navigation systems such as FriendFeed or Blip.fm, and he can also write a blog on which his latest pics will automatically appear.
We can read about a lot of exemplary cases, from which it emerges: a girlfriend in the morning, looking at a flood of photos of her mutual friends, can easily figure out who her shabby boyfriend spent the evening with, or the company can fire his employee just because he tells his honest opinion about the top management on his blog: one thing is for sure, the concept of private life has been completely reconsidered today.
One who lives an online life consists of what he shows of himself, so we could define the basic thesis behind the behavior of today's youth.
And if you want to hide something, or at least avoid Google’s monopoly, you have the option (starting with Scroogle, which uses Google’s search system, but deliberately leaves no traces).
For example, a large number of people do not intentionally register on community sites to avoid being able to find them. Google’s online applications from text editor to photo editor and news portal can be exchanged for alternative versions that are not connected to giant server parks and that do not make us the best possible profile.
