Intelligent car imitates the flight of a bumblebee
What would be the best method of developing technologies capable of preventing collision, if not imitation of obstacle detectors occurring in the natural world?
For example, the bees.
The initial strategic idea of the surprise project, presented at the CEATEC trade fair in Japan, was inspired by the engineers from Nissan. It was about how to build a new generation of collision avoidance systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has designed a biomimetic robotic control system, the BR23C, a robotized mini-car equipped with bee characteristics, with the ultimate goal of helping to create a system that can eliminate all collisions.
"During the flight, each bee creates its own personal space of oval shape, which is actually very similar to our safety protective packaging," Kazuhiro Doi, the brand's general manager for technology PR and research and development, explained at the exhibition.
Compound eyes play an important role, allowing bees to see more than 300 degrees in all directions.
To copy the function of the compound eye, engineers reached for the idea of a laser rangefinder.
It identifies obstacles at a distance of up to 2 meters before BR23C in the field of view of 180 degrees, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which immediately transforms into an operation aimed at preventing a collision.
The obstacle is captured in a fraction of a second, then the robotized car begins to imitate the movements of the bee and by turning the wheels to the extent necessary to prevent a collision immediately changes direction.
Unlike any existing system, this maneuver is entirely instinctive.
"If that were not the case, a robotic car would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," explains Toshiyuki Ando, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the robotic car project.
It must respond instinctively and immediately, as this technology suits the most vulnerable and innermost layer of the safety protective packaging, within which a collision is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what the bee is doing to avoid other bees.
This process should not take longer than a blink of an eye.
Unlike bees, however, this movement cannot be upwards, downwards or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional and only in the direction in which the wheels can be turned.
Instead of the endless possibilities offered to bees when avoiding, only the possibility of rotation, acceleration and deceleration was used in the case of a robotic car.
BR23C uses lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and have a higher energy density, meaning they have a longer life span than lithium-ion variants.
According to Ando, instinctive, intelligent responses are important, not the ability to process, much less store data.
This mechanism must process and respond to only a few incoming signals per second.
It does not need to be stored and reacted to using intuitive logic based on data from previous maneuvers, so it constantly uses only memory of a few kilobytes.
It does not require memory with gigabyte or megabyte capacity.
This is the first step in developing an immediate avoidance technology that Nissan estimates could make its way into production vehicles within a decade.
Another option may be the connection of the unit with the GPS satellite navigation system, which would lead the motorist to the specified final destination after avoiding obstacles in the way.
