The $700 billion economic rescue package bill, which is to be split into several instalments and aims to buy back poor-quality bank loans, is already in writing.
Half of the amount will be used in the first round.
After further talks, which ended Saturday after midnight U.S. Eastern Time, congressional officials reached an agreement in the days-long $700 billion bailout debate.
“We have made significant progress,” said Nancy Pelosi, the Democratic Speaker of the House of Representatives, who said the only thing left is a deal.
The compromise on the package was also supported by both presidential candidates Barack Obama and John McCain.
Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson said: “The program will work and will be effective, but further steps must be taken.”
The written version of the package was published before the opening of Asian markets on Sunday at 8 p.m. Washington time (i.e. on Monday at 2 a.m. Central European time), but it did not cause any particular rise in the stock markets.
The House of Representatives will vote on the draft law in the name of the Emergency Economic Stabilization Act of 2008, which is to establish the program on Monday, after which it will be the turn of the Senate.
President George W. Bush spoke with Pelosi on Saturday evening, after which news of the deal was also welcomed by the White House.
"We are pleased with the progress made last night and greatly appreciate the efforts of both sides to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy," White House spokesman Tony Fratto said in a statement.
The program, after all, differs from the Bush administration’s original proposal to spend $700 billion to buy bad-quality mortgage-backed securities.
It is now possible to spend a maximum of half of $700 billion in the first round, so that $250 billion will be used immediately after Congress decides on the matter as expected on Monday, and the Treasury Department will buy mortgage-backed securities that are assessed as of poor quality, the fate of the remaining $100 billion will then depend on the decision of the president.
The program will be controlled by a special committee, which will also include the chairman of the Federal Reserve Bank.
Spending the second half of $700 billion will depend on the next decision of Congress.
According to the law, the Ministry of Finance can apply a combined tactic: it can simultaneously buy back poor-quality loans, mortgages and securities secured by mortgages, or other "toxic" loans.
The purchase can take place both within the auctions and directly, the competent representatives of the ministry said.
The law will allow the companies concerned to participate in an insurance program, in which the Ministry of Finance will provide them with a guarantee for the funds constituting a cause for concern, for which the companies will then pay a price corresponding to the amount of expected damage.
As Henry Paulson said, the law provides the necessary resources to meet the urgent demands of the U.S. financial system of up to $700 billion, whether it be a large-scale purchase of bad funds, their insurance, or to prevent the systemic risk associated with the collapse of one of the major financial institutions.
"We will take the necessary steps to be ready to implement the law as soon as it is signed."
On the contrary, the heads of banks who are in trouble and waiting for state aid can count on the government to reduce the severance pay - which in overseas slang is simply called "golden parachute".
Their payments will be limited only in certain cases, in addition, these restrictions will depend on the method of assistance provided by the Ministry.
In essence, the restriction means that if the Ministry purchases as part of the auction, a tax surcharge will be imposed on gold parachutes if the fallen bank directors are not sent straight to retirement.
In the case of direct repurchase of poor-quality loans, the government will aggressively intervene to ensure that the money for management is not excessive.
It should be added that the already existing contracts for gold parachutes will not change, the restriction applies only to new contracts, which is supposed to be another incentive to participate in the program.
"This is the first time in U.S. history that a legal limitation on CEO remuneration will be in place," said Barney Frank, chairman of the House Financial Services Committee.
In addition, the state will have the right to acquire a share in the participating banks, thus reducing the risk of taxpayers, because once the economy and the rescued bank get on their feet, they can also profit from this transaction.
In the next five years, the president must submit a proposal to Congress on how the expected losses from the financial sector can be repaid to taxpayers.
Of course, there were also voices on both sides expressing doubts about the plan.
"That's not what the American people asked us to do, because that's not what taxpayers' dollars will protect," Republican Congressman Darrell Issa said.
His Ohio Democrat colleague Mary Kaptur believes that it was precisely those responsible for the collapse of Wall Street who urged the enactment.
Industrial prices continue to rise
Domestic sales prices in the industry increased by 0.1 percent in August 2008 compared to the previous month, and by 12.9 percent in August 2007, the Central Statistical Office reported.
Export sales prices in the industry were higher by 1.1 percent compared to July 2008, decreased by 3.9 percent year-on-year.
Production prices in industry, as a cause of changes in domestic and export prices, were higher by 0.7 percent compared to the previous month, increased by 3.2 percent year-on-year.
Domestic sales prices in the industry increased only marginally compared to the previous month, by 0.1 percent.
Domestic sales prices in the manufacturing sectors also increased slightly by 0.1 percent compared to July.
The largest increase in prices occurred in August 2008 in the leather and footwear industry (2.8 percent), mainly due to a month-on-month increase in prices in the industry of bag and saddlery products by 4.6 percent and footwear production by 2.5 percent, respectively.
The higher price level of plastic and chemical raw materials caused a significant monthly increase in prices in the chemical materials and products industry (1.6%).
Price reductions have occurred in the oil processing sector (1.4 percent), the production of electrical machinery and apparatus (0.9 percent), as well as - to a minimum - in the woodworking sector (0.1 percent).
Prices in the paper industry and publishing and printing activities have not changed.
In other sectors of the manufacturing industry, we have measured a price increase in the range of 0.2 - 0.9 percent.
In the sector of electricity, gas and water production and distribution, which is of great importance in the domestic sales of industry, prices increased by 0.3 percent in August, mainly due to the continuing effect of the officially determined increase in gas prices occurring from 1 July.
In the 12-month comparison of domestic sales in individual sectors of the processing industry, prices increased the most in the professional oil processing sector (32.4 percent).
In the metalworking sector, a 13.2% increase was observed, in the production of food, beverages and tobacco products, which has a decisive impact, and an 11 percent increase in prices.
Price reductions have occurred in the textile and textile products industries (2.5 percent) and in the electrical machinery and apparatus industries (0.3 percent).
In other manufacturing industries, the rate of price growth was between 0.6 and 9.1 percent.
Overall, prices in the manufacturing industry rose by 10.2 percent last year.
Prices in the electricity, gas and water sectors exceeded the previous year’s prices by 18.7 percent.
In terms of segmentation by sector, domestic sales in August showed the highest monthly price increase (0.7%) in the sectors involved in the production of tangible assets.
In the consumer goods sectors, prices increased by 0.3 percent, in the energy-processing and downstream sectors, prices did not change compared to the previous month.
The largest price increases relative to the same month of the previous year were observed in the energy processing and downstream sectors in August 2008 (16.8%).
In the consumer goods sectors, we measured a price increase of 6.8 percent, while in the case of tangible assets, prices fell by 1.4 percent.
Export sales prices of industrial products measured in forints increased by 1.1 percent in August compared to the previous month, falling by 3.9 percent in the 12-month comparison.
Our domestic currency weakened by 1.7 percent against the euro in one month, then by 7.1 percent against the dollar, strengthened by 7.5 percent against the euro in August 2007 and by 15.9 percent against the dollar.
