“Scientific findings,” he continues, “show clear risks and need to be addressed quickly.
The most important thing is that we need to encourage consumers and make this information public.
We must continue to re-examine existing control systems in the light of this scientific finding in order to make them fully effective and keep pace with the new technology."
Brussels has asked the Independent Scientific Committee to investigate the problem, given the high use of portable musical instruments and the growing number of young people exposed to noise of this origin.
"Scientists," concluded the executive official of the European Union, "confirm that there is a need to worry and now the European Commission will examine together with the other members and parties who raised the problem what measures could possibly be put in place to better protect children and young people from exposure to noise caused by portable musical instruments and similar devices."
There is currently a European safety standard that limits the noise level of portable musical instruments to 100 dB, but there is growing concern about hearing damage that may be caused by overexposure to similar forms of noise.
It is possible to greatly limit these damages by seeking solutions such as reducing the level and duration of exposure.
In its opinion, the EU Scientific Committee states that users of portable music devices, if they use loud music (more than 89 decibels) for only five hours a week, will exceed the current limits corresponding to the maximum permitted noise in the workplace.
Those who listen to music in such conditions for an extended period of time risk permanent hearing loss after five years.
This problem should affect 5-10% of users of such devices, and their number can be estimated between 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
