Elites in Danger
This phenomenon was manifested a few days ago when the Chamber of Representatives voted against the $700 billion rescue plan presented by the White House: a large proportion of Americans were more interested in punishing Wall Street than saving the economy.
This is confirmed by yesterday’s New York Times, which informs us that the current crisis is tearing apart the Republican Party, increasingly divided between its old East Coast soul, more moderate, more accommodating to federal institutions and the business community, and its new soul, which is on the contrary conservative, hostile to “those from Washington” and to the world of finance, strong especially in the states in the middle part of it.
A soul that has arrogantly demonstrated itself by the vote I spoke of at the beginning.
But this thing just quoted is just an example of the changes, the big changes that the current economic earthquake is already showing: not just in the United States, but throughout the West, and perhaps not just here.
Both in the U.S. and Europe, this crisis seems to be acting as an accelerator for phenomena that have been incubated for a long time, which are becoming more and more intense in the new climate and are finally coming to light.
The first of these phenomena is the re-actualization, the extraordinary recovery of the market, the double category of state-power in relation to a certain re-nationalization of the economy.
Indeed, the crisis is a crisis for the banking of financial institutions, which, of course, have strong bonds abroad, but in which, above all, the budgets of people and families living in one country, in one state, are included to the greatest extent.
This has also created a political problem for those who run it: that is, how to respond to the difficulties and protests of people and families who are, among other things, voters.
In short, the crisis appears to be global in economic terms, but almost exclusively national in political terms.
Political internationality seems to be fundamentally out of the question, or that it has little to add: the European Union, which as always is divided between different interests and different national strategies, has given obvious proof and cannot decide on a common political line.
And so everyone is waiting for the intervention of the government of each individual state, rescue plans, market recovery, new rules and, above all, the distribution of funds: when we get into distress, only the states have the economic means, the amount of financial resources, to be able to try to put everything in order.
It also possesses the necessary means and authorizations to use them: two sources of immense value, under certain circumstances, which perhaps no market and no international organization will ever be able to dispose of to such an extent.
This new phase, which the crisis places on the state-national element, is, moreover, in perfect harmony with the growing importance which it attempts to attribute to the last economic progress to one factor closely connected with it: territorial jurisdiction.
Paradoxically, while we were convinced that we had entered the kingdom of the sieve, an increasingly sophisticated technology, immaterial, while we were convinced that global finance was already destined to rule the world, we suddenly realized that our future would have to deal more and more with such little immaterial things as water, grain, diesel.
All things, who would have thought, can be transported from one place on earth to another, but in any case they are connected, absolutely, to a limited space, territory.
So, whoever becomes their ruler certainly has many more cards up his sleeve than who is not and who has the misfortune of living in a place without grain, without diesel and without water.
I come to the second news, which, however, predicts a break.
He who speaks of territory, of the state, of government, inevitably speaks of politics, that is, of leadership.
Given the economic crisis, it seems that two convergent phenomena are being created.
On the one hand, the realization that there is an objective need for authoritative leadership, a request for someone who can take on the situation.
On the other hand, a wave of discredit towards existing leaderships, especially economic ones, which turned out to be equally unsatisfactory and full of dark places.
And together, something even deeper and, in a sense, disturbing: discredit, impatience, a sense of incompetence and absence that seeks to dominate the entire ruling class in more and more Western countries.
For it seems that convictions are spreading more and more among the broad masses of the population than their actions are the same as the ideas of the hitherto popular elite, as their way of feeling and being, as their culture in the true sense of the word, that the elite has already surpassed its time and is indifferent to the opinions of the majority.
The demand for leadership simply feeds one branch from the underground, but a strong movement to eliminate the ruling classes and the traditional political order manifests itself in sudden electoral “resistances” or in unexpected changes in collective sentiment in the last and most recent time, from the conservative rise in Austria-Bavaria to the fall of the Labour Party in the UK, to the rise of the US Congress.
We have the impression that the traditional elites, their parties, their programs, but also their ceremonies, their newspapers, their accredited intelligence, some would say their format, have more and more problems to understand, that is, to represent, which, not from today, is being created in the deep layers of Western societies, and that the economic crisis is re-strengthening, growing, potentially overblown.
Before this it would be an exaggeration to speak of a permanent "mass revolt".
But we certainly can't say that it means keeping our eyes open.
