When energy is born from the waves, the big ones come into play.
It is an infinite deposit that covers more than 70% of the Earth’s surface and is now being discovered by the world’s major energy companies.
Waves, currents, tides, and tides are the new sources of inexhaustible energy upon which the eyes of giants like Chevron have clung, now trying to reach out to these sources.
The possibility of generating energy from sea movements has been studied for more than a century, and in the 1970s, in the context of the first oil crisis, research intensified.
When the price of oil went down around 1980, the idea of using marine energy went sideways. But now environmental organizations and a new increase in the price of oil gave the sector a new impetus.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London stated in 2007 that about 15 percent of the world's electricity consumption could be covered by the use of sea waves.
That amount would be twice the amount of energy currently produced in nuclear centers.
In addition, there are also currents and tides.
Giants are attacking.
The company that put its money on marine energy was Enersis, which agreed in 2005 to build facilities in northern Portugal.
When this intention was announced, it seemed like a huge revolutionary step.
After two years of betting on marine energy, more and more companies are betting on marine energy rather than traditional energy.
"Chevron is studying ocean energy technology," said a spokesman for a company linked to the United States oil giant in the economic daily newspaper The Wall Street Journal, "and they are thinking about the possibility of working with us."
The cooperation we are considering involves obtaining a permit from the U.S. Energy Commission, which is necessary for the launch of a marine energy project in Alaska.
We cannot underestimate this signal, especially considering that it is in Alaska that the US continues to extract oil, and recently President Bush has come up with a plan for a new drilling.
In addition to Chevron, Verdant Power Inc. of New York and Ocean Power of New Jersey, and the amounts invested so far, although not known in detail, are showing increasing interest, according to observers.
Technology needs to be developed.
Experts talk about the technology, which is still in its infancy, because it is not known what impact the use of marine energy will have on the environment.
For now, facilities in Portugal and some in Scotland are small in size and do not appear to cause major ecosystem problems.
For greater energy production, however, it is necessary to use technologies with a greater impact on the environment.
The methods are different: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of buoys that are connected to each other.
The force of the waves, which moves with the buoys up and down, is changed with the help of cylinders and cylinders to the hydraulic pressure inside these buoys.
The pressure spins the turbine, which supplies energy to the generator.
Energy comes ashore through submarine cables.
For the time being, there are four facilities of this type in the project phase, which are only waiting for federal approval, and part of the energy could be used for military purposes.
By contrast, Verdant Power is already producing power for the shopping mall and parking lot by using six subsea turbines in New York's East River.
The movement of water during high tide and low tide causes the turbines to rotate, feeding the generator with this rotational movement.
Verdant said they have a long list of clients who are waiting for the necessary authorizations because of the possibility of using this energy.
